<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Zambia-AIDS     09-03 0139</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Zambia-AIDS,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Burns Herself to Death After Taunts About AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young woman died after dousing her
clothes in kerosene and setting herself afire because of taunts and
accusations that she had AIDS, news reports said.
   Christine Lubebe, 21, died from burns at a hospital in the
Central province of this East African nation, the reports said
Friday.
   The Times of Zambia quoted Freda Lubebe as saying her sister was
accused by youths in a bar of being a prostitute with acquired
immune deficiency syndrome.
   The dead woman was buried Thursday, the newspaper said. It did
not give the date she burned herself.
   AIDS is a deadly affliction in which a virus attacks the body's
immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and
cancer. In Africa, it is spread mainly by heterosexual contact.
</TEXT>
