<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 0600EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Airlines     09-03 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Airlines,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paper Says State Airlines Plagued By Poor Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's leading daily said today that poor
service on the state-run airline ``brings shame to the country and
its ongoing reforms.''
   The People's Daily criticism of the Civil Aviation
Administration of China came three days after a CAAC jetliner
skidded off the runway at Hong Kong's airport and crashed into the
harbor, killing six crew members and one passenger.
   It was CAAC's second fatal accident this year. In January, a
CAAC jet crashed near the southwestern city of Chungking, killing
all 108 people aboard.
   The newspaper did not mention the accidents, concentrating on
the ``deep-rooted problems'' in service.
   ``All CAAC employees, from leaders to ordinary staff members,
should feel ashamed. They should try hard to improve the situation
as quickly as possible if they have an iota of national
self-respect,'' it said.
   The daily, official voice of the Communist Party, said in one
instance the destination of a scheduled flight out of Canton in the
south was suddenly changed to Chengdu in the southwest without
notifying the passengers in advance.
   The Beijing office of a foreign company wrote four letters to
book tickets without getting a response, it said. ``If this service
is not poor, what is?''
   CAAC passengers also complain of frequent flight delays and
cancellations, poor food and the refusal of CAAC employees to say
when a delayed flight will leave, the report said.
   The daily said CAAC, which in recent years has initiated a
program of decentralization to make its operations more efficient,
is finally acknowledging the need for improvement.
   ``Admitting backwardness means that CAAC is waking up to the
realities,'' it said.
</TEXT>
