<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TroutWreck     09-03 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trout Wreck,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fish Trip Ends in Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN HOME, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,500 rainbow trout bound for
Oklahoma waters ended up in the hands _ and probably the skillets _
of bystanders after the truck carrying the tasty fish overturned,
officials say.
   The truck from the Norfork National Fish Hatchery was traveling
down a northern Arkansas highway Friday with the load of trout for
Oklahoma when a vehicle headed the other way crowded the road, said
State Police Cpl. Bob Roten.
   The truck pulled to the right to give the oncoming vehicle some
room, but a rear wheel ran off the road and into a ditch, Roten
said.
   The driver's efforts to get the truck back on the road shifted
the load of 2,500 trout in a 1,000-gallon tank of water, and the
truck overturned, the corporal said. The tank, and the fish, fell
off the truck.
   In an agreement involving the Oklahoma Wildlife Department, the
hatchery and a state Game and Fish officer, authorities gave the
fish away to people at the scene rather than let them spoil.
</TEXT>
