<1ST_LINE>r w PM-S&LRescue     09-03 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-S&L Rescue,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks On Rescue of California S&L Expected To Resume</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators and representatives of the
Robert M. Bass Group of Fort Worth, Texas, are expected to resume
talks today on the rescue of American Savings and Loan Association
of Stockton, Calif., according to a government official.
   Karl Hoyle, a spokesman for the Federal Home Loan Bank Board,
said early today that face-to-face meetings between representatives
of the two parties had recessed but that negotiations had not
broken down. But, no announcement was forthcoming even though the
parties met late into the night.
   Speaking shortly after midnight, he said, ``I suspect we won't
talk again until later today.''
   On Thursday, the bank board had described the negotiations as
``intensive.''
   Industry sources say the two sides are discussing a proposal
that could become the largest rescue ever of a single S&L. Sources
say the proposal would have the Bass Group contribute $500 million
and the bank board adding up to $2 billion in assistance.
   To date the largest S&L bailout is the $1.3 billion infusion
last November into Vernon Savings and Loan Association in Texas.
   American is owned by the Irvine, Calif.-based Financial Corp. of
America, the second-largest thrift holding company in the nation
with $30.2 billion in assets as of June 30.
</TEXT>
