<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 0322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Biaggi-Disclosure Bjt   09-03 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Disclosure, Bjt,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biaggi Discloses Up to $1.7 Million in Assets, Faces $8 Million in
Fines</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to include budget designator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Mario Biaggi last year owed
somewhere between $30,000 and $100,000, according to his federal
financial disclosure form, but that's small change compared with
the roughly $8 million in fines he faces after two federal
convictions.
   Biaggi, a Democrat who represented part of the Bronx and
Yonkers, N.Y., in Congress for nearly 20 years, resigned his seat
Aug. 5 after being found guilty of extorting bribes from the
Wedtech Corp.
   Wedtech was a Bronx machine shop that grew into a
multimillion-dollar military contractor before being forced into
bankruptcy.
   Biaggi also was convicted on other charges, including that he
had filed false financial disclosure statements in the past by
failing to include the $50,000 cash and $3 million in stock he
allegedly demanded from Wedtech in exchange for his clout in
Washington.
   Biaggi reported income and assets totaling between about
$769,000 and $1.7 million last year on his financial disclosure
form. He listed debts of between $30,000 and $100,000 in 1987.
   Members of Congress are required to report annually on their
income and assets, but only within broad ranges.
   As in recent years, Biaggi's latest disclosure made no mention
of Wedtech stock and included no gifts to the congressman.
   His 1987 report, which had been due with the clerk of the House
of Representatives on May 15, was not received until Aug. 18. The
congressman had been granted three extensions in light of the
Wedtech trial, which began in March and ended Aug. 4.
   Biaggi continues to maintain his innocence and the verdict is
under appeal. Sentencing is scheduled for Nov. 18, at which time
the 70-year-old ex-congressman faces up to 146 years in prison and
$7,422,000 in fines. The judge also ordered Biaggi to forfeit
$350,000 in ill-gotten gains.
   In a separate trial last year, Biaggi was convicted of accepting
an illegal gratuity in the form of paid Florida vacations. He was
sentenced to 2{ years in prison and fined $500,000. Appeal of that
case was denied in early August, but Biaggi's attorneys have
petitioned for a rehearing.
   Biaggi's 1987 income included $7,000 in fees from his former law
firm, Biaggi and Ehrlich, for unspecified services. Biaggi and
Ehrlich also reimbursed the ex-congressman for an unspecified
amount of telephone expenses.
   Biaggi sold his partnership in the firm in 1979 for $320,000 to
be paid over time at 7 percent interest. He was supposed to receive
$30,000 per year for the period Jan. 1, 1980, through Dec. 31,
1988, according to his disclosure forms. But in 1987, Biaggi only
received between $2,501 and $5,000 from the agreement.
   Other members of the firm, namely Bernard Ehrlich and Biaggi's
son, Richard, also were defendants in the Wedtech trial. Ehrlich
was convicted of racketeering and Richard Biaggi was found guilty
of bribe receiving, mail fraud and tax fraud.
   The elder Biaggi, who was a New York City policeman from 1942 to
1965, collected $16,837 on his police pension last year, the form
also showed.
   Biaggi's stock holdings ranged from more than $505,000 to in
excess of $1 million. He also purchased stocks worth between
$20,000 and $85,000 in 1987 while he sold securities worth between
$10,000 and $30,000.
   The forms are not a very good indicator of net worth, however.
Members are not required to list holdings such as real estate,
unless it is sold or rented out during the year in question. They
also do not have to report cars, boats or other valuable assets.
</TEXT>
