<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     09-03 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Heading West After Eastern Swing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential nominee George Bush is
heading to the West Coast for more campaigning after an Eastern
swing in which he took his Democratic rival Michael Dukakis to task
on environmental issues.
   On this Labor Day weekend, the traditional symbolic beginning of
the election campaign, Bush arranged to meet with reporters today,
then go on Monday to California where he is to tour a San Diego
fish plant and visit Los Angeles. On Tuesday, he heads to Oregon
and Washington state.
   Bush spent Friday turning up the political heat on Dukakis,
trying to burn the Massachusetts governor on issues involving the
environment. The vice president stood on polluted New Jersey
beaches, went along on a Delaware River crab harvesting operation,
and worked the sidewalk crowds in New Castle, Del.
   Later Friday, he attended the wake for Prince George's County,
Md., policeman Mark Murphy, who was shot accidentally by a fellow
officer. Murphy was well known to Bush's Secret Service detail as
part of an emergency services team helping with security at Andrews
Air Force Base in Maryland.
   Bush went on the attack at the beach in Belmar, N.J., where
medical waste and sewage has washed ashore in the past and forced
it to be closed.
   In remarks to a few hundred supporters, the vice president
accused Dukakis of seeking to pollute New Jersey waters by asking
the federal government for permission to dump Massachusetts' waste
106 miles offshore in 1985. A later agreement allowed Massachusetts
to dump farther out to see, beyond the continental shelf.
   Bush said he had a question for Dukakis: ``Why did you pledge a
clean ocean to the people of New Jersey when your own state applied
to pollute it?''
   As for himself, Bush said, he would work to ``ban ocean dumping
forever'' while making ``the enforcement of Superfund, the
prosecution of polluters, and the cleanup of toxic waste a top
priority.''
