<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Beating     09-03 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Beating,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Shown Beating Suspects In Television Footage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of Britons watched television news
footage of two men being pummeled by police officers after their
car was pulled over for a traffic violation.
   Independent Television News said the incident was filmed by a
cameraman who said he was testing his equipment Thursday night in
the village of Brynsiencyn, Anglesey, North Wales, about 230 miles
northwest of London.
   The footage, first broadcast Friday on HTV in Wales, and later
in a national broadcast, showed four police cars with flashing
lights pull over a small car.
   Two men were dragged from the car. One lay curled up on the
pavement. As he tried to rise, officers pushed him to the ground.
Both men were kicked and punched repeatedly.
   Viewers of the Welsh broadcast could hear one screaming as an
officer sat on his chest and punched him in the face, according to
Press Association, the British domestic news agency.
   It said that when the police became aware of the cameraman, they
rushed toward him but he that escaped with the film.
   One officer was suspended and an investigation was launched into
the incident, said a spokesman for the North Wales Police in nearby
Colwyn Bay. The position of other officers will be reviewed as the
investigation progresses, the spokesman said.
   ``We would seek to bring this to an early conclusion,'' said
Assistant Chief Constable John Owen. He said the vehicle had failed
to stop and was being driven at a dangerous speed.
   The civilian men were identified Friday as Brian Owen, who was
charged with reckless driving, and Michael Williams, charged with
assault with intent to resist arrest. Both are in their early 20s
and residents of nearby Newborough.
   The pair have lodged a formal complaint against the North Wales
Police, said their lawyer, John Meredith.
   Meredith said Owen suffered bruising under the eye, a swollen
nose and injuries to the back. Williams was injured in the mouth
and face, he said.
   Ieuan Wyn Jones, the member of Parliament representing the area,
called for an independent inquiry into the beating.
   ``If I am not satisfied, I shall take the matter to the Home
Office,'' he said, referring to the government department that
overseas police procedures in Britain.
</TEXT>
