<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Argentina-Falklands     09-03 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Argentina-Falklands,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Recommends Lengthy Jail Terms For Leaders Who Started
War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal prosecutor recommended
members of a former ruling junta, including former President
Leopoldo Galtieri, be imprisoned from 15 to 20 years for starting
the 1982 Falklands War.
   Prosecutor Luis Moreno Ocampo told a Federal Appeals Court on
Friday that Gen. Galtieri, Adm. Jorge Anaya and Brig. Gen. Basilio
Lami Dozo were responsible for the loss to Britain of the 74-day
war and for the deaths of 712 Argentines killed in the conflict.
   In May 1986, the Armed Forces Supreme Council convicted all
three of misconduct for their command of the three military
branches in the war, which began after Argentine forces invaded the
disputed islands.
   The military court sentenced Galtieri to 12 years in military
prison, Anaya to 14 and Lami Dozo to eight. They were allowed to
keep their ranks pending the outcome of an automatic appeal to
civilian court.
   All three sought to have their convictions overturned, but
Moreno Ocampo asked for a 20-year prison term for Galtieri; 18
years for Anaya and 15 years for Lami Dozo.
   Also on trial are three lower-ranking officers who were
acquitted by the Supreme Council, Argentina's highest military
tribunal.
   Moreno Ocampo requested five years' prison for Vice Adm. Juan
Jose Lombardo; four years for Gen. Mario Menendez; and three years
for Gen. Omar Parada.
   Menendez was military governor of the Falklands during the war
and surrendered Argentine forces to the British on June 14, 1982,
at the capital of Port Stanley.
   Parada commanded army troops on the islands. Lombardo was
commander of navy forces in the South Atlantic.
   At issue is how the war was conducted. A military inquiry found
that Argentine troops were poorly trained, equipped and led.
   The inquiry focused in part on the decision by Anaya, a former
navy head, to virtually withdraw the fleet from combat after the
cruiser General Belgrano was sunk by a British submarine; and on
the strategy and tactics of Argentine soldiers on the islands.
   Since the appeal began July 26, Moreno tried to show that
Argentina's military rulers did not anticipate Britain's military
response, nor prepare for it.
   Defense attorneys argued that Argentina almost won the war, and
charges of incompetence were unfounded.
   Also, defense attorneys claimed Britain consistently refused to
negotiate the islands' return to Argentina, and such political
considerations should be taken into account.
   Britain's claim to the Falklands dates to 1833. Argentina claims
it inherited the islands, which it calls the Malvinas, upon
achieving independence from Spain in 1810.
   About 1,900 people, mostly sheep ranchers and fishermen, live on
the windswept islands.
   At war's outbreak, Argentina's economy was deteriorating and
opposition rising to the junta. The war was seen as a last-ditch
attempt by the military, in power since a 1976 coup, to gain public
support.
   The humiliating loss to Britain was followed by the military's
decision to turn over the government to an elected civilian leader.
In October 1983, attorney and human rights leader Raul Alfonsin was
elected president.
   A ruling by the four-man appeals court was not expected for
several weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
