<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BusCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0448 09-03 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0448,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Die, 17 Injured In Bus Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with death count revised
downward to one, authorities now not sure of conditions of injured,
edits to conform; picks up 7th graf pvs, ``A landing ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tour bus with 42 people aboard rolled
off a muddy highway Friday in a remote area near the Canadian
border, killing one person and injuring at least 17, a state police
spokesman said.
   The accident near Eagle 110 miles east of Fairbanks near
Alaska's border with the Yukon Territory probably occurred shortly
before 3 p.m., when the bus ``went off a veritable cliff'' on the
Taylor Highway, State Troopers spokesman Bill Farber said in
Anchorage.
   One person died and 17 seriously injured people were taken to
Fairbanks Memorial Hospital, Farber said. Another 20 were in Eagle
awaiting transportation to an Army hospital at Fort Wainwright near
Fairbanks, where they were to be checked for injuries.
   Farber earlier said two people died and 15 were critically
injured, but said later that the conditions of the injured were not
known. He said communications with the accident scene were poor.
   The extent of injuries among the remaining five people on the
Gray Line of Alaska bus was not immediately known.
   Eight helicopters provided by the military, Alaska State
Troopers and a private company were sent to pick up victims, Farber
said.
   Fairbanks Memorial sent a team of doctors to Tok, which is 180
miles southeast of Fairbanks and 125 miles southwest of Eagle.
   A landing strip in the area was determined to be capable of
handling a C-130 airplane, and one of the aircraft was on standby
at Eielson Air Force Base in case additional help was needed,
Farber said.
   Rescuers were hampered by steep terrain, and three to four
people were required to carry just one accident victim up a hill,
he said.
   ``It's a real remote area,'' Farber said. He said the bus ran
off a serpentine stretch of highway pelted by rain for several days.
   Gray Line of Alaska said it sent an investigative team to the
scene and could offer no immediate information about the crash or
the passengers. A spokeswoman said most if not all of the
passengers were adults. The bus left Eagle Friday and was bound for
Tok on the company's Klondike Explorer tour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
