<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SeattleBlackout 2ndLd-Writethru a0741 09-03 0851</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seattle Blackout, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0741,0872</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Powerless Downtown Seattle Braces For The Return Of Electricity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with power now not expected to
be restored before Sunday, street lights back on; picks up 3rd
graf, ``If thousands ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVE BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Utility and fire officials coping with downtown
Seattle's three-day power outage had a new worry Friday: what will
happen when the electricity goes back on, jolting equipment from
bank computers to appliances?
   ``It could be like opening floodgates,'' said Hugh McIntosh of
Seattle City Light, whose crews hoped by Sunday to relight a large
part of the city's retail and financial core, which has been
without power since Wednesday.
   Utility crews rigged lines from street lights outside the
affected area to provide street lighting Friday night for the first
time since the outage began. Traffic signals, however, remained
dark.
   If thousands of computers, lights, air conditioners and
appliances are on when power comes back, the load on the circuits
could cause a sudden voltage dip, McIntosh said.
   ``It would be like halftime during a ball game when everyone
flushes all the toilets and the water pressure drops,'' he said.
   That could damage computers and other appliances with
microprocessors, including videocassette recorders, televisions and
microwave ovens, he said. Further, it could trip sensitive
monitoring equipment at City Light's substation, causing another
blackout.
   ``The voltage drop can really foul up computers,'' McIntosh
said. ``It's not a fire threat, but we're concerned that it could
damage our equipment that controls power frequency _ and could
possibly cause the power to go back off.''
   McIntosh earlier said that refrigerator motors could be damaged
when power was restored, but said Friday evening he was
subsequently told that was not the case.
   Officials are concerned that if the extensively repaired
underground wiring has a short when power is turned back on, it
could lead to another fire like the one Wednesday that knocked out
power, McIntosh said.
   Officers at Great Northwest Federal Savings and Loan, located
one block south of where an underground electrical fire knocked out
power for hundreds of businesses, turned off their computer as a
precaution.
   ``We've turned off everything and intend to leave it that way
until things are back to normal,'' said Dianne Backus, division
manager.
   Like many downtown businesses, the savings and loan scaled back
operations in order to keep open at all. Ms. Backus helped staff a
card table where customers IDs were checked before they were let
into the saving and loan, two at a time, to make withdrawals for
the weekend.
   ``This is banking the way it used to be,'' she said. ``We're
taking down every transaction by hand and every couple of hours run
to one of our branches and enter everything into the computer.''
   Roy Davis, spokesman for the Seattle Fire Department, estimated
90 percent of the businesses were closed by the worst power outage
in city history.
   Regular checks were being made of fire alarm systems and at
apartment hotels where officials feared guests might be using
candles or gas-powered camping stoves.
   ``If we find anyone doing that we're going to cite them,'' said
Davis. ``Frankly this situation is new to us and we're a little
nervous. We've got several cars patrolling just to look for fires.''
   The party atmosphere of the first 24 hours without power faded
as hotel guests got over the novelty of being issued complimentary
flashlights and instead complained of 15-story climbs to rooms.
   ``I began to notice a little soreness in my calves yesterday,''
said Janet Hardin of Eaton, Ohio, a guest at the 40-story Westin
Hotel's south tower, which had just one of three elevators in
service.
   Westin officials tried to accommodate most guests in the hotel's
north tower where there was air conditioning to offset temperatures
in the mid-90s.
   ``Most people haven't complained about the heat,'' said Dior
Hill, public relations manager for the luxury hotel. ``To people
from Atlanta and Houston this is nothing unusual.''
   Downtown streets were slightly less crowded than usual. Sidewalk
generators drowned out the sounds of city buses and cars directed
by traffic cops standing in for powerless stoplights.
   By Friday afternoon' City Light crews had replaced about a mile
of cable burned by an unexplained fire in an underground vault.
Another mile still had to be replaced before the utility could turn
the power back on.
   Utility spokeswoman Julia Greenlee said superintendents of about
20 buildings would be asked to be on hand to turn their air
conditioning and other major equipment back on piece-by-piece to
help control surges.
   There have been no injuries reported during the power outage and
heavy police patrols have been credited with preventing break-ins.
   Police Lt. Al Lorette said 35 to 40 officers extra officers were
assigned to patrol the blacked-out area, in addition to about 40
officers who normally work downtown.
   ``You see what's on top of that car?'' Seattle police Officer
R.E. Lutz asked, gesturing to a police car with red and blue lights
on its roof. ``That's why there's no looting.''
</TEXT>
