<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     09-03 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Asked to Order Toyota Warranty Disclosure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumers advocacy group believes owners of
cars manufactured by Toyota should know about secret warranties the
Japanese company has on its vehicles and has asked the Federal
Trade Commission to order the automaker to directly notify
carowners.
   ``The Toyota documents clearly show that the company has an
internal policy that systematically reimburses consumers for
failure of specific components beyond the written warranty,'' said
Sam Cole of the Center for Auto Safety.
   ``Certainly ... every Toyota owner should be made aware,'' of
the policy, he said.
   The center, often critical of the automakers and their
regulators, on Friday filed its petition with the FTC. A year ago
the center asked the FTC to require all manufacturers to disclose
secret warranties.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>800,000-Ton Corn Sale Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says the Soviet
Union has bought an additional 800,000 metric tons of U.S. corn for
delivery during the 1988-89 marketing year.
   The new purchase agreement announced Friday follows by one day
the kickoff of the marketing year and the sale of 100,000 tons of
corn to the Soviets, also for delivery in 1988-89.
   With corn prices currently averaging about $2.49 per bushel at
the farm level, the two sales could have a farm value of around
$88.4 million.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 900,000 tons of
corn would be about 35.5 million bushels.
   Officials did not say whether the new sales would count under
the current five-year grain supply agreement between the two
countries that is set to expire Sept. 30.
   Negotiators are currently trying to work out a new pact, or an
extension of the current agreement, to take effect Oct. 1.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Relatives Of KAL 007 Victims Mark Anniversary Of Aircraft Downing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of Americans who died in the Soviet
downing of a Korean airliner in 1983 marked the fifth anniversary
of the tragedy with a call for a full congressional investigation
into unanswered questions still surrounding the incident.
   ``It would be a dangerous precedent to let this matter fade into
oblivion,'' said Nan Oldham of Bethesda, Md., the mother of a
27-year-old man killed in the air disaster.
   ``It is fitting, indeed imperative, for Congress to conduct a
full-scale investigation,'' said Mrs. Oldham, co-chair of a family
members' organization, during a Friday news conference. ``Armed
with its subpoena power and the right to examine more than 1,200
still-classified documents, Congress can uncover the truth.''
   ``We feel betrayed by our government whose silence in this case,
rationalized by the questionable claim of national security
concerns, is beginning to resemble a deliberate cover-up,''she said.
   Sixty-three Americans were among the 269 people who died aboard
Korean Airlines Flight 007 when it was shot down on Sept. 1, 1983
after passing over Soviet territory while on a flight from
Anchorage. The plane had strayed more than 350 miles off course.
</TEXT>
