<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador-Duarte     09-03 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Duarte,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Duarte Says He'll Continue Governing Despite Illness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte,
who has terminal cancer, told his countrymen he feels strong enough
to continue in his post.
   But in a Friday night address, he implied that if he becomes
incapacitated by his illness he will step down.
   ``I will continue working, continue governing, as long as I feel
I have the capability to do so,'' said Duarte, who looked gaunt and
whose voice sounded strained.
   ``If one day I feel incapable of doing that, my historic duty
would then be to make a decision,'' he said.
   ``I feel I have sufficient strength and capacity,'' the
62-year-old president said.
   Duarte's comments, broadcast nationwide on all radio and
television stations, were his first public statements since
returning Aug. 10 from Washington, where he received chemotherapy
for liver cancer.
   Duarte, who has lost 35 pounds during the past month and much of
his hair, spoke seated at a conference table surrounded by his
Cabinet ministers. He met with them for an hour Friday, the first
Cabinet session he has presided over in several weeks.
   Duarte's doctors said when the liver cancer was diagnosed in
June that he had between six and 18 months to live. The president's
five-year term ends June 1, 1989.
</TEXT>
