<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 0446EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea-Kim     09-03 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Kim,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korean Opposition Leader Hopes For Stability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung said
today the military will never again seize power in South Korea, and
he said he is confident the nation will achieve political stability
after the Olympics.
   Kim also told The Associated Press that he doubted radical
students or communist North Korea would attempt to disrupt the
Olympic Games in Seoul.
   The head of the opposition Party for Peace and Democracy said
the political situation was complicated and uncertain, but he
believed democratic progress would continue after the Olympics.
   ``We feel that after the Olympic Games, our political situation
can be stable,'' he said.
   The armed forces will never rule the country again because the
South Korean people became too strong and mature to endure any more
military governments, Kim said.
   ``No general can dream of such a thing. Even if he takes power
through a military coup it cannot last long,'' he said.
   Kim played down concerns expressed by many Koreans about the
possibility of a government crackdown after the Olympics. Some
opposition leaders fear the government is being moderate to avoid
alienating world opinion during the Olympics but that there may be
a crackdown after the Games.
   South Korea has been ruled for most of its 40-year history by
authoritarian military and civilian leaders.
   The opposition leader said President Roh Tae-woo assured him
Wednesday that the military would declare its neutrality in
politics. ``We have agreed only democracy can solve our problems,''
he said.
   Kim did not say whether the opposition would try to force Roh to
hold a referendum on whether or not he should stay in power. Roh
said last year he would call for a refendum of some kind after the
Olympics.
   ``We are not in a hurry to expel him (Roh) from the political
arena,'' Kim said.
   Roh, a former general, defeated Kim and rival opposition leader
Kim Young-sam in December presidential elections. Roh replaced
former President Chun Doo-hwan, who took power with military
backing in 1980. The elections were called after massive
anti-government demonstrations.
   Kim said Roh must investigate and settle issues such as alleged
corruption in the Chun administration.
   The opposition leader also said he doubted radical students
would try to disrupt the Sept. 17-Oct. 2 Games with violent
demonstrations. ``The students know they will not be supported by
our people,'' he said.
   Kim said North Korea would not disrupt the Olympics because it
would be condemned worldwide.
   North Korea has said it will boycott the Olympics if it is not
allowed to be a co-host of the Games. The North's demand has been
rejected, but South Korean officials fear their communist archrival
may try to disrupt the Olympics.
   The one serious threat to the Olympics would appear to be
international terrorists, some of whom have ties with North Korea,
Kim said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
