<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 0448EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Sasso-Profile     09-03 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sasso-Profile,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sasso Offers A Familiar Hand To A Political Friend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Sasso, who had been there for Michael Dukakis
for a long time until about a year ago, is there again in time to
offer a familiar hand to his political friend.
   Dukakis once said Sasso is ``like a brother'' to him. ``He is a
very talented person,'' Dukakis told reporters Friday, adding:
``John didn't do anything that was illegal or dishonest. It was a
mistake in judgment.''
   ``I'm delighted to be back as part of the general election
team,'' Sasso said Friday, ``because I've always been committed to
Michael Dukakis.''
   Amid reports the campaign was sagging, Sasso returned to the
Dukakis fold as vice chairman of the Democratic presidential
nominee's effort after nearly a year away from the action.
   Sasso, one of the Massachusetts governor's most trusted aides,
resigned in the ``attack video'' incident that involved Sen. Joseph
Biden of Delaware who had been one of Dukakis' rivals for the
nomination.
   Sasso dropped out after admitting he had circulated a videotape
showing Biden using a British politician's words without credit.
Biden's campaign suffered and later ended following admissions of
plagiarism and false claims about his academic record.
   In coming back to work for Dukakis, Sasso apologized for the
incident and said he did not mean to raise questions about Biden's
character. Dukakis said Biden ``could not have been more gracious''
when told of Sasso's return. ``I continue to support Governor
Dukakis,'' Biden said in a statement.
   Sasso promised to ``adhere to the very high standards'' of
Dukakis and pay close attention to the words and actions of
Republican presidential nominee George Bush.
   ``There are contrasts and weaknesses that are issues in this
campaign,'' he said, adding: ``I will not shy away from pointing
those contrasts out.''
   Said Dukakis: ``Almost a year ago, John Sasso made a very
serious mistake.
   ``He's paid the price,'' the governor added.
   Sasso, 41, first met Dukakis on a train platform in 1978 at a
low point in the governor's political career. Dukakis, who had
sought renomination, had just lost to Democrat Edward J. King, and
Sasso offered to help if Dukakis ever decided to get back into
politics.
   Two years later, with Sasso aboard, Dukakis rode the comeback
train to win re-election in 1982. Dukakis installed Sasso as his
chief secretary, serving as his top contact with legislators and
handling media relations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
