<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 0428EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-YonkersDeseg Bjt   09-03 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yonkers Deseg, Bjt,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yonkers Lawmakers Continue To Defy Judge Over Desegregation Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four defiant Yonkers city councilmen held fast
to their refusal to bargain with a federal judge, sending their
troubled city toward bankruptcy for continuing to resist a
court-ordered desegregation plan.
   One day after he was given a green light by the U.S. Supreme
Court, U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand on Friday reimposed fines
on the city just north of New York that can soon amount to $1
million a day and bankrupt it in short order.
   The judge then unsuccessfully tried to work out a settlement in
informal talks with the recalcitrant councilmen, but the discussion
ended within an hour with the two sides apparently no closer to
agreement.
   In 1985, Sand found the city guilty of racially segregating
housing for four decades. The City Council has refused to approve
plans to build low- and moderate-income housing to aid
desegregation.
   The nation's highest court Thursday night affirmed the crippling
levy Sand imposed in his effort to bring the city into line with
the law.
   However, the court stayed the $500-a-day personal fines and jail
terms Sand had imposed on the four councilmen.
   Sand said that despite the stay, the councilmen ``still have a
responsibility to the citizens they represent who will bear the
brunt of these (city) fines.''
   Sand ordered the city to pay the fines accumulated over the
Labor Day weekend _ $192,000 _ on Tuesday. As previously promised
by Sand, more than $85,000 of the money will be earmarked for
Yonkers public schools and to guarantee the payment of interest on
city bonds. The balance will go to the U.S. Treasury and is
non-refundable.
   Sand then called on lawyers for all parties in the
long-simmering legal battle to meet with him privately ``to explore
informally some ideas we have for a possible solution of this
crisis.''
   Lawyers for both sides and city officials emerged tight-lipped
from the brief meeting in the New York courtroom.
   ``It was not successful,'' said Mayor Nicholas Wasicsko, who
favors complying with Sand's housing desegregation order.
   Michael Sussman, attorney for the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, said there was no progress and
called it a ``hostile discussion.''
   ``I haven't changed my position. I will do what I have to do,''
said Henry Spallone, one of the defiant councilmen.
   Sand told city attorney Michael Sculnick he could renew his
request that the judge stay the city fine ``if between now and
Tuesday when the $192,000 is due and payable, I am satisfied that
we have reached a point which makes it appropriate that the fines
be suspended or payments delayed.''
   The city's fine started at $100 on Aug. 2 and doubled daily for
a week until it was stayed pending appeals. The city has paid
$12,700 so far. The fine reaches its $1-million-a-day cap next
Friday.
   Gov. Mario Cuomo said he would direct the state's Emergency
Financial Control Board on Tuesday to begin making the substantial
reductions in city spending that will be required by Sand's order.
The board took control of the city's finances Aug. 9.
   Even with the cap on the fine, Yonkers, the state's
fourth-largest city with a population of 200,000, would be bankrupt
by mid-November, city officials said.
   Cuomo, who had been reluctant to get involved, said last week he
would initiate removal proceedings against the four councilmen if
the fines were reimposed against the New York suburb.
   The control board passed a resolution the same day saying it
would seek criminal charges against the four if the fines were
reinstated. The allegations would be that the four jeopardized the
city's fiscal condition, violating the law that established the
control board.
   However, Cuomo spokesman Gary Fryer said Friday that for the
time being the governor would not attempt to oust the councilmen.
   The Supreme Court's order late Thursday stayed a lower court
ruling that had upheld contempt citations against the four
councilmen, who had been paying their $500-a-day fines and would
have been subject to imprisonment this weekend.
   On Aug. 1, the council voted 4-3 against a desegregation plan
that would provide incentives to build 800 units of moderate-income
housing throughout the city. Sand found the councilmen in contempt
the next day and since then, three additional efforts to pass the
housing plan have failed.
</TEXT>
