<1ST_LINE>u a PM-DeltaCrash-VictimServices Bjt   09-03 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta Crash-Victim Services, Bjt,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Who Died In Crash Remembered For Selflessness</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN2</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Today's services scheduled to begin at 3 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people, many wearing the uniforms of
three airlines, turned out to remember a veteran Delta Air Lines
flight attendant as funerals began for the 13 victims of the crash
of Flight 1141.
   ``Delta is just sort of a family,'' said Delta flight attendant
Karen Bounds. ``I'm coming out of respect.''
   Earlier Friday, more than 2,200 mourners gathered for services
for Phil and Thelma Vogel, who were instrumental in helping the
homeless in Dallas.
   About half of the approximately 300 people at the funeral Friday
night for attendant Rosilyn Marr were uniformed Delta flight
attendants and pilots, who were joined by a handful of flight
attendants from American Airlines and Braniff Airways.
   ``Ros was such a vivacious and outgoing kind of person and to
know her was to like her and to feel like you knew her well,'' the
Rev. Paul Ramler told mourners at Restland Funeral Home.
   Ms. Marr, 43, had flown with Delta since 1965 and was involved
in finding homes for stray pets, friends said.
   Three more funerals, including one for another flight attendant,
were scheduled today. Arrangements were pending in other cases.
   All 13 victims were from Texas.
   Ninety-five people survived when the Boeing 727, en route to
Salt Lake City, plunged to the ground and burst into flame seconds
after takeoff Wednesday at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport.
   At the service for the Vogels, many of the mourners who filled
Congregation Shearith Israel synagogue said they knew the couple
personally.
   ``I look at you and I know you feel as I do. We feel ill
physically, spiritually, mentally, emotionally,'' said Rabbi Jordan
Ofseyer, who called the couple ``two of our finest, most useful
friends.''
   Vogel, 69, and his wife, 67, were traveling to Canada for a
vacation. They were remembered as tireless leaders of the Jewish
community and the city who worked quietly and without publicity.
   ``Even if she wasn't well, she called to see how you were
doing,'' said Geraldine Sobel, who knew the couple since 1962.
   In March 1987, the Dallas Jewish Coalition for the Homeless
opened a day-care center where homeless families searching for work
could leave their children. Mrs. Vogel was the driving force that
organized the coalition, a group of 26 Jewish organizations, while
her husband, a certified public accountant, helped with the group's
books.
   ``It's going to be hard without Thelma, but we can't let her
down because it was her dream,'' said Doris Budner, who with Mrs.
Vogel was co-coordinator of the coalition. ``I suppose we'll never
know, but I think the reason they are not here today is because
they were trying to help other people (out of the plane). That
would be like her.''
   Besides helping with the homeless coalition, Vogel was a member
of a number of civic, professional and religious organizations. He
was president of the Jewish Federation of Public Accountants and
president-elect of the Texas Association of Accountants.
   The couple had two grown sons.
   ``All of us are poorer for the tragic deaths we memorialized
this day,'' said Rabbi Gerald Klein. ``But, oh, how rich we are
because they lived among us.''
</TEXT>
