<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 0528EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Meat     09-03 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Meat,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pravda Says Government Overstated Amount of Meat Available to
Consumers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government officials have overestimated the amount
of meat available to the public for years by padding per capita
production statistics with animal fat and meat byproducts, Pravda
reported.
   In a lengthy article, the Communist Party daily reported serious
shortcomings in the country's meat production.
   Thursday's article told Soviets what most already knew, that the
Soviet Union doesn't produce enough meat to feed its people
properly. The story was part of a wider campaign launched since a
Communist Party meeting earlier this summer focusing attention on
food and consumer goods shortages and calling for a crash program
to improve supply and distribution.
   Pravda cited government statistics as claiming that each Soviet
consumed 141 pounds of meat last year, near the annual level of 154
pounds health officials recommend.
   It turns out the meat consumption figure for 1987 includes 1.6
million tons of animal fat and ``subproducts of a second category''
not containing meat, Pravda said. The ``subproducts'' include
heads, legs, ears and tripe. People were eating 13 pounds a year of
this kind of ``meat,'' Pravda said.
   The actual per capita consumption figure was closer to 128
pounds, Pravda said, but even that was unevenly distributed around
the country.
   The method of calculating the figure was drafted during the
``years of stagnation,'' the catchwords for the rule of Soviet
leader Leonid I. Brezhnev. The statistics were inflated to
``convince ourselves how well were were living,'' the newspaper
said.
   Under Brezhnev, and even before, government officials overstated
output of factories and farms they supervised to qualify for
bonuses and give the impression, often false, that they were
meeting government-set plan targets.
   The article was part of the campaign for ``glasnost,'' or
greater openness on some issues, encouraged by Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880903-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 0529EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissAmerica     09-03 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Miss America,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 51 contestants in this year's
Miss America Pageant checked out the competition as they spent
their first full day together.
   The competitors from the 50 states and the District of Columbia
were individually ushered around as they signed in Friday, posed
for photographers and chatted with reporters.
   Each day leading up to the Sept. 10 televised finale in the 62nd
pageant, the competition that starts Wednesday grows just a little.
   One of the first unofficial contests is the fashion parade upon
arrival.
   The outfits worn by the women as they arrived Thursday in this
seaside gambling resort were eye-catching, even if only the
hostesses and media were watching.
   Leather suits, stylish hats, patent leather high heels and belts
that emphasized tiny waists appeared to be the trend.
   But Friday was the big chance to make an early impression on the
other contestants, so even practice leotards were adorned with
jewelry and fingernails were perfectly manicured.
   Of course, most contestants don't openly admit they are sizing
up each others' chances at winning the crown and scholarship money.
   ``It's really neat. When you get a bunch of overachievers
together, we're all anxious to meet each other, not necessarily to
size up the competition,'' said Miss Iowa Tiffany Ann DiBernardo.
   ``We have a common bond,'' said Miss Nebraska Jodi Sue Miller.
``There were 78,000 girls in preliminary competitions narrowed down
to 51, so it's neat to compare goals _ and there are lots to
compare.''
   Miss North Carolina Lee Beaman said she was surprised ``at how
friendly the whole group was'' when the contestants met for the
first time. ``I was expecting a little more of conspicuously
checking out the competition.''
   Miss Vermont Julie Tidd conceded that the competitive spirit
``perhaps will come as time goes on this week.''
   The contestants already have had several opportunities to leave
marks of individuality. Each contestant wrote a greeting on a
wooden cutout of their state, which then was attached to a giant
wall map.
   Some focused on their talents, such as Miss Oklahoma Lori Lee
Kelley, a singer who wrote, ``Oklahoma is Opera-tunity!''
   Others focused on timely issues, such as Miss Iowa, who wrote,
``No drought about it _ success still grows!''
   In the middle of it all, three pigeons flew into the cavernous
Convention Center and decided to visit.
   In horror, the Miss America hostesses tried to shoo the birds
away, fearful that they would leave their ``calling cards'' on the
new pink carpet.
   ``If you do anything on this carpeting, I'll ...'' said hostess
Betty Frisch, chasing after a bird with a wagging finger.
</TEXT>
