<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PennyParking     09-03 0130</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Penny Parking,0135</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Penny Parking Perishes In Mass. Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorists in this western Massachusetts
town are faced with a whopping 400 percent increase in parking
meter costs _ from a penny to a nickel.
   Officials this week converted 425 penny parking meters to
instead require a nickel for the privilege of parking for half an
hour.
   The penny meters generated more than $8,000 anually in revenue,
said Department of Public Works Superintendent John Bean.
   Revenues are now expected to top $40,000 a year, Bean said.
   The conversion of the penny meters was first suggested by the
town's planning committee as a way to increase the turnover of
parking space, Bean said.
   The penny parking meters were believed to be among the last in
western Massachusetts.
</TEXT>
