<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     09-03 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UPLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robin Whelan is a real earth mother.
   Mrs. Whelan, who already has three sons born in quick
deliveries, gave birth to her fourth son on the hospital lawn when
she was unable to make it to the delivery room in time.
   Mrs. Whelan said that when she and her husband, Russell, arrived
at San Antonio Community Hospital on Wednesday night, nurses told
them their baby wasn't due until after midnight.
   ``I was afraid to go home for the mere fact I've had other
children so fast,'' said Mrs. Whelan, 26.
   So the Whelans sat in their van in the parking lot at the
hospital in San Bernardino County about 40 miles east of Los
Angeles.
   It wasn't long before the baby was on his way, so Whelan ran
back to the hospital to get help.
   ``I couldn't get back in the hospital because the door was
locked,'' said the 27-year-old father.
   Finally, he returned with a nurse. Mrs. Whelan, who found
herself unable to walk, was laid down on the lawn.
   A short time later, Chad Anthony Whelan, weighing 6 pounds, 10
ounces, was born. Mother and son were in excellent condition,
hospital officials said.
   When Whelan cut the umbilical cord, Mrs. Whelan and her baby
were covered with grass, he said.
   ``There I was, naked with all these people standing around,''
Mrs. Whelan said. ``I was just thankful it was at night and they
hadn't just watered the lawn.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quiet, retiring giant panda, more inclined
to munch foilage than make a play for the spotlight, has become the
top draw at the Cincinnati Zoo.
   More than 60,000 people have tickets to see Chia Chia, the giant
male panda who goes on display today at the zoo, during his
three-month stay in a 5,000-mile journey to a breeding program in
Mexico.
   Chia Chia will be the most popular display ever at the zoo,
which will use profits from the exhibition for conservation of the
endangered pandas, the zoo said.
   ``It's the most charismatic and popular of all (the animals),''
said zoo Director Ed Maruska.
   The panda was flown from the London Zoo to Chicago, then taken
by van Friday to his temporary home in Cincinnati.
   The Toledo Zoo ran into opposition when it put two giant pandas
from China on display this summer, drawing charges it was
exploiting the animals. The World Wildlife Fund and the American
Association of Zoological Parks and Aquariums tried to prevent the
animals from being shipped out of Shanghai, but failed to get a
court order.
   Cincinnati's zoo avoided such controversy because it's only a
stopping-off point for an animal involved in a breeding program,
and because of its agreement to use money from the exhibit for
panda breeding and conservation programs.
</TEXT>
