<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Singapore-Election     09-03 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Singapore-Election,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voting Brisk In Singapore Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters today chose a new generation of leaders
for this prosperous Asian city-state, but the prime minister since
1959 was not expected to retire from power.
   Voting was compulsory for those 21 or older and a heavy turnout
was expected before the polls closed at 8 p.m. (8 a.m. EDT). About
1.45 million people were eligible to cast ballots in the districts
contested. Election day was declared a national holiday.
   The governing People's Action Party was expected to win the
parliamentary election by a big margin. Prime Minister Lee Kuan
Yew, who will be 65 on Sept. 16, was expected to step down in favor
of First Deputy Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, 46.
   Lee, who called the election ``truly a watershed,'' has been
prime minister since 1959 and more than half of the 2.6 million
people have known no other leader.
   Lee is to retain the powerful post as the governing party's
secretary-general, and, although he has expressed disinterest, is
still regarded as the most obvious candidate to be the country's
first elected president.
   The proposed elected presidency remained the key issue as the
nine-day campaign wound down Friday. It would replace the current
appointed ceremonial post with a president holding veto power over
spending the nation's ample financial reserves and nominations to
senior civil service and judicial positions.
   At stake in the election were 70 of the 81 seats in the recently
enlarged Parliament. The other 11 seats were captured unopposed by
the governing party when nominations closed Aug. 24.
   Nominees from seven opposition parties and four independent
candidates mounted a challenge. The last Parliament had 79 seats,
76 held by the governing party, one by the opposition and two
vacant when it was dissolved.
   There are 42 traditional single-member voting districts. But in
a new wrinkle, all parties entered in 13 constituencies had to
nominate a panel of three candidates _ at least one of whom had to
be from an ethnic minority group. Voters select a team of three,
each of whom gets a separate vote in parliament.
   The population is 76 percent Chinese, about 15 percent Malay and
6 percent Indians.
   Elections were called 16 months before a new election was
required.
   Diplomatic analysts said the government hoped to take advantage
of a booming economy and full employment with the early elections.
</TEXT>
