<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     09-03 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Hit Nation's Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms swept ahead of a slow-moving cold front across the
upper Great Lakes and middle Mississippi Valley today, bringing
heavy rain, strong winds and hail as big as golf balls.
   On Friday, the thunderstorms dropped heavy rain and hail in
parts of Wisconsin, Illinois, Iowa, Indiana and Missouri.
   In Wisconsin, golf ball-size hail pounded parts of Monona and
smaller hail hit spots in the northeast and south central parts of
the state.
   In southeast Missouri, thunderstorms brought heavy rain, leaving
some roads near Oran, Delta and southern Bollinger County under
water.
   Showers and thunderstorms hit western sections of Texas, as well
as the north and central parts of the state. Almost 3 inches of
rain fell in little more than an hour in Bonham, causing local
flooding. Some of the storms diminished in strength today.
   Thunderstorms also fizzled over northwest Arizona after whipping
up strong winds and heavy rains.
   Showers and thunderstorms were reported in eastern Texas,
Oklahoma, the Ohio Valley, the Gulf Coast, Florida, Alabama and the
lower Mississippi Valley.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from Texas
and the Gulf Coast to the lower Mississippi Valley, the Ohio
Valley, the eastern half of the Great Lakes and northern
Appalachians; numerous thunderstorms from northeast Texas to the
Ohio Valley and the lower Great Lakes; and scattered showers and
thunderstorms through Florida and mountainous areas of Arizona.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s through northeast
Minnesota and upper Michigan; the 70s along the Pacific Coast, as
well as in the northern and central Plains, western Texas, the
central and southern Rockies, most of the middle and upper
Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes, the northern Appalachians and
northern New England; in the 90s in the Pacific Northwest; between
100 and 110 degrees over the desert Southwest and inland valleys of
California and Oregon; and in the 80s through the rest of the
nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 46
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 94 degrees at Yuma,
Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 72 cloudy; Boston 66 partly cloudy; Buffalo 68
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 72 foggy; Cincinnati 71 cloudy; Cleveland
67 showery; Detroit 69 partly cloudy; Miami 81 fair; New York 67
fair; Philadelphia 61 fair; Pittsburgh 62 cloudy; Portland, Maine
62 fair; Washington 64 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 55 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 74 fair; Denver 59
fair; Des Moines 64 fair; Indianapolis 68 foggy; Kansas City 66
fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 57 fair; Nashville 75 partly cloudy; New
Orleans 78 rain; St. Louis 73 partly cloudy.
   _West: Anchorage 47 partly cloudy; Las Vegas 84 fair; Los
Angeles 69 fair; Phoenix 92 fair; Salt Lake City 67 cloudy; San
Diego 70 fair; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle 70 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 64 partly cloudy; Toronto 68 cloudy.
</TEXT>
