<1ST_LINE>u a PM-FiresRdp     09-03 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fires Rdp,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Halted Outside Montana Town, Utah Homes Threatened</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos XWS 1,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters held back flames threatening a town near
Yellowstone National Park, Utah homeowners cleared dry brush around
their property, and residents of Western states were warned to stay
out of the woods over Labor Day weekend.
   ``Ninety percent of the people out there this weekend will be in
areas where they shouldn't be building fires in the open,'' said
Kathy Albert of the U.S. Forest Service. ``They must be in
designated fire pits. We're pleading with people to be careful with
their fires.''
   Woods and fields also burned in Washington, Oregon, Montana,
Wyoming, Idaho and California as the worst wildfires in 30 years
raged on.
   In West Yellowstone, Mont., bulldozers, helicopters and
backfires stalled the advance of an 118,800-acre fire in the
neighboring park. Flames were a mile away Friday.
   Crews wrapped fire-retardant foil around the tiny town's
telephone poles, and rows of fire trucks tested their hoses in
parking lots.
   The firefighters received help from 50 farmers and others from
Ashton, Idaho, who hoped to lay two miles of pipeline, then pump
water from the Madison River to wet down the tinder-dry forest
floor between the town and the blaze.
   ``We shut our grain combine down to come up here,'' said Frank
Clark, 35, one of the volunteers. Despite losses the farmers will
suffer from being away at harvest time, ``it's never a hardship to
help out,'' he said.
   Although firefighters called their efforts a qualified success,
gusty winds swept a swath of flame south of town Friday, and a wind
change forecast for Monday also raised concern.
   Officials warned of a possible evacuation, and some guests in
the town's many motels checked out early. Most of the town's 750
permanent residents were sticking it out, though many filled gas
tanks and packed their cars in case.
   ``In my judgment this community is very defensible,'' Denny
Bungartz, the fire's incident commander, told a somber crowd of 60
townspeople Friday.
   The fire is one of six major blazes that have charred more than
550,000 acres of the 2.2 million-acre park this summer.
   Firefighters elsewhere in Montana mobilized to save a historic
dude ranch in the path of a giant fire north of Yellowstone. Fire
information officer Dave McMorran said three fire engines and a
20-member crew stood by at the Silvertip Ranch.
   In Utah, officials evacuated three mountain homes Friday night
and dug trenches around them as a runaway 550-acre brush fire raged
in a scenic canyon east of Salt Lake City. Residents of 40 other
homes were warned they may have to evacuate today.
   Many homeowners used chainsaws and weed trimmers to clear a
buffer zone around their homes. Others sat on their roofs, garden
hoses within reach.
   Officials asked residents in fire-prone states to stay out of
the woods this Labor Day weekend to reduce the danger of new blazes.
   In Idaho, the restrictions in certain forests included a ban on
firewood cutting for personal use and restrictions on chainsaws and
use of vehicles.
   Many forests in Oregon were closed to recreational use. Montana
officials urged residents to find alternatives to woodland
activities. Weyerhaeuser Co. and ITT Rayonier timberlands were
closed to the public in Washington.
   Smoke from fires in northeast Washington was so bad that a state
road was closed and another was limited to local traffic for 37
miles.
</TEXT>
