<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 0826EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-MailStrike     09-03 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Mail Strike,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Overseas Mail Halted By Postal Walkouts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walkouts by postal workers at 92 sorting offices
disrupted mail service within Britain for a fourth day today and
halted international mail for the first time during the strike, the
workers' union said.
   The union representing 140,000 workers involved in sorting and
delivery mail is protesting pay bonuses that differ by regions and
the hiring of temporary employees to handle the mail backlog.
   Alan Tuffin, general secretary of the Royal Mail and the Union
of Communications Workers, said 15,000 of his members were off the
job Friday ``and by this morning that had risen to about 40,000.''
   A union spokesman said four large London sorting offices were
shut down by walkouts today, including Britain's largest foreign
mail depot.
   The spokesman, who demanded anonymously, said the dispute had
spread to Scotland, where about 3,500 postal workers walked out in
Glasgow after three colleagues were suspended for refusing to
handle letters brought in from strikebound Liverpool in northern
England.
   The union said all of south Wales and part of north Wales were
affected by the dispute, along with most of northwest and southeast
England. The post office later confirmed the union's information.
   Royal Mail receives about 50 million pieces of mail a day. A
backlog of more than 100 million pieces of mail began building
Wednesday with a 24-hour nationwide strike by sorters and
deliverers, the first since 1971.
   On Thursday and Friday, thousands of workers stopped work again
after Royal Mail brought in temporary employees to help clear the
backlog.
</TEXT>
