<DOCNO> AP880903-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 0911EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0452 09-03 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Taking Aim At Quayle On Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new to update with appearance today; picks up 3rd
graf, In a brief.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis chided Republican rival George Bush today for
referring to the increase in the unemployment rate as
``irrelevant.''
   ``Yesterday, unemployment went up,'' Dukakis told an
early-morning rally. ``Another 200,000 people without jobs.
   ``The vice president said it was irrelevant. Those are people,
those are our fellow citizens. It's not irrelevant.''
   During campaign appearances Friday, Dukakis took aim at Dan
Quayle, the Republican vice presidential nominee.
   ``Dan Quayle doesn't know very much,'' Dukakis said when told
the Indiana senator had called him a big-spending liberal.
   In a brief exchange with reporters at the Sioux Falls airport,
Dukakis said: ``People like Quayle call themselves conservative.
They haven't voted for a balanced budget in their life.''
   In an interview with regional reporters at the airport in
Spokane, Wash., earlier in the day, the Democratic presidential
nominee responded sharply when asked if Quayle is qualified to be
vice president in an administration headed by Republican George
Bush.
   ``I don't know of anyone who thinks Dan Quayle is qualified to
be president,'' he said.
   ``Look at his record in the Congress, his lack of experience,''
said Dukakis. ``I don't think he was selected because he was
qualified to be president.''
   Dukakis was winding up a pre-Labor Day campaign swing with a
stop at Ellis Island, the first stop in America for his Greek
immigrant parents more than 75 years ago.
   Dukakis' father landed there in 1912 at the age of 16. His
mother was 9 when she arrive in America less than a year later.
   His mother, Euterpe, and New York Gov. Mario Cuomo were among
those joining Dukakis for the trip to the island in the New York
harbor where generations of immigrants landed.
   Dukakis' emphasis on his immigrant heritage is a major factor in
his bid for the support of blue collar voters, many of whom are
also first- or second-generation Americans.
   Although voters who retain strong identification with their
ethnic roots have traditionally been heavily Democratic in their
preference, they shifted allegiance to Republican Ronald Reagan in
1980 and 1984.
   The campaign swing included appearances in California, Oregon
and Washington and a brief sleep-and-refueling stop Friday night in
Sioux Falls.
   During stops in Portland, Ore., and Spokane, Wash., on Friday,
Dukakis ridiculed the idea of naming Quayle to head the war on
drugs in a Bush administration.
   ``Is there anybody here today, is there any citizen in the
United States of America, who thinks Dan Quayle is qualified to be
the nation's drug czar?'' he asked, drawing cheers and hoots from
partisan crowds.
   He repeatedly contrasted what he described as Quayle's
inexperience with the long career of Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, the
Democratic vice presidential nominee.
   ``Isn't it nice to have a Democratic nominee for vice president
whose qualifications have never been questioned by anybody?'' he
said at a rally at a steelworkers union hall in Spokane.
   ``We're going to have a vice president who's been a leader'' in
the U.S. Senate, he told a rally in Portland, Ore.
   During a brief tour of a Kaiser Aluminum Co. plant in Spokane,
Dukakis wrote in big block letters on a roll of aluminum, ``MADE IN
USA.'' Workers cheered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
