<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Badminton-Slaying     09-03 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Badminton-Slaying,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gandhi Foe Arrested In Slaying Of Badminton Champion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A political foe of Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi was arrested today in connection with the slaying of India's
top badminton player after newspapers alleged he had an affair with
the sportsman's wife.
   Sanjay Singh, 32, was arrested in Lucknow, the capital of Uttar
Pradesh state, 250 miles southeast of New Delhi, said an official
of the Central Bureau of Investigation. The official cannot be
identified under briefing rules.
   The bureau, patterned on the United States' FBI, took over
investigations into the July 28 slaying of Syed Modi, the national
badminton champion, after a request from the Uttar Pradesh
government.
   Modi, 28, was gunned down by an assailant using a Colt
.38-caliber revolver as he stepped out of a Lucknow sports stadium
where he had gone for his customary evening round of practice.
   Newspapers, quoting unidentified sources in the Central Bureau
of Investigation, said last month that investigators had found
evidence of an affair between Modi's widow Ameeta and Singh. The
evidence followed days of searching for a motive to the slaying,
the sources said.
   On Aug. 16, an associate of Singh and three other people were
arrested on murder charges in Modi's death.
   Ameeta Modi was arrested on charges of conspiring to murder her
husband five days later. But she was released on bail by a
magistrate within three days when she said there was no one to care
for her 6-month-old daughter.
   In India, people charged with murder usually are not granted
bail.
   The allegations in the newspapers drew angry reactions from
Singh, a former Gandhi ally. ``This is the worst kind of political
vendetta,'' he said in New Delhi last week. ``The Prime Minister
and his coterie are using government agencies to intimidate the
opposition. Their plan is to discredit me in order to give Rajiv
Gandhi a victory in the next general elections.''
   Singh is not a political star outside Uttar Pradesh but he is
the scion of the former royal family of Amethi, Gandhi's
parliamentary constituency. Royal titles were abolished in 1971 but
members of ruling families still command considerable influence
over their former subjects.
   Singh was the campaign manager and chief architect of Gandhi's
mammoth victory from Amethi during the last national elections for
Parliament in 1985. The Prime Minister drew more than 90 percent of
the votes cast.
   But the two fell out last year. Singh resigned from the
governing Congress Party and vowed Gandhi will not win the next
election in Amethi.
   Singh's arrest follows several rounds of questioning by
detectives and a search of his Lucknow residence. The search drew
criticism from several opposition politicians because it was shown
on state-owned national television.
   ``They want to try Sanjay Singh through electronic media,'' said
Arif Mohammed Khan, who, like Singh, resigned from the Congress
Party year. ``They want to finish him.''
</TEXT>
