<DOCNO> AP880903-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 1036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WheatonMen     09-03 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wheaton Men,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheaton College Welcomes First Men in School's 154-Year History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As 18-year-old Dan Wolotsky unpacked his
clothes on orientation day at Wheaton College, he said he had
hardly thought about being in the first class of men admitted to
New England's oldest women's college.
   Until he received a letter from an upperclasswoman.
   ``She wrote me saying, `I hope you bring a stuffed animal
because everyone has one,''' recalled Wolotsky of Hightstown, N.J.
``That's when it dawned on me what I was doing. My uncle told me to
bring a bullfrog _ he said that'll scare them.''
   Wheaton is welcoming male students this fall for the first time
in its 154 years, a decision reached after a bitter stuggle with
alumnae who opposed the change. Seventy-five men will be in this
year's freshman class of 402.
   School officials said the decision to admit men to Wheaton is
part of the trend to make single-sex colleges coeducational because
newer generations of students demand it.
   ``The interest in going to a women's college has diminished,''
said Gail Weaver, director of admissions and student aid.
``Ninety-five percent of our women come from coeducational settings
where they've had the opportunity to be editor of the school paper
or class president and they've never felt discriminated against.
They feel there's no reason to buy into the argument that they need
to go to school with just women to succeed.''
   Weaver said fewer than 100 women's colleges remain in the
country. Almost half are small, church-related schools, she said.
   The transformation of Wheaton, which is 35 miles south of
Boston, to a coeducational school was rocky.
   Some alumnae balked when they learned of the January 1987
decision to admit men. They claimed that many alumnae donated to
the school in recent years without knowing of the plans eventually
to admit men.
   The matter went to court where, a probate judge ruled in June
that Wheaton must notify all donors that it will return their
donations if requested.
   ``It's a very sad day,'' said Mary Anne Marsh, 31, a 1979
graduate and one of the alumnae who protested. ``It's diminishing
what little opportunities are left to women who want to attend
small, liberal arts schools.''
   Administrators said little has been changed to accommodate men
on the idyllic 378-acre campus of brick buildings and a white
chapel.
   They were, however, forced to buy longer beds.
   And packages of toiletries distributed to incoming freshmen on
orientation day now include a separate package for men which,
several women noted, does not contain the laundry detergent given
women and has ``better razor blades.''
   The people most excited about men coming to Wheaton were, not
surprisingly, incoming women.
   ``I wouldn't be here if it wasn't coed,'' said Susan Howland,
18, of Lincoln, R.I., as she unpacked in her dormitory room
Thursday. ``I think it's going be fun. Maybe a little odd because
there aren't that many men.''
   ``I came basically because it was going coed,'' said Nadja
Drazien, 18, of Montreal. ``I think our society means that women
have to learn how to work alongside men.''
   School officials also had reason to be enthusiastic.
Administrators said enrollment has increased 30 percent since they
decided to admit men. The college will house 1,150 students this
year. Tuition is $16,700 a year.
   Like other men, Wolotsky is a little concerned that only one
sport will be available to men this fall: cross country. Officials
are building a new athletic facility that eventually will mean a
bigger sports program for men.
   Mark Sweet, 19, standing in line to register, said he wanted to
come to Wheaton because his two aunts and grandmother are alumnae.
He said he has endured some teasing from friends about being sought
after by women on campus.
   ``My first response is to tell them to shut up,'' said Sweet.
``I'm paying a lot to study and get a good education. My social
life is important but that's not what I'm paying $17,000 a year
for.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
