<1ST_LINE>u i PM-AirShowMemorial 3rdLd-Writethru a0513 09-03 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Show Memorial, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0513,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Leads Service For Air Show Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with death toll climbing to 51, number
of people hospitalized falls to 165. ADDS LaserPhoto number. No
pickup.
^LaserPhoto KAI4</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Richard von Weizsaecker
today led mourners in a memorial service for victims of the
Ramstein air show disaster. Officials raised the death toll to 51
after two more people died.
   ``Pain and sorrow are tearing at the hearts of so many people,''
the Rev. Helmut Pflanz told about 400 West Germany, Italian and
American mourners crowded into the Roman Catholic Church of St.
Nicholas in Ramstein.
   ``We are deeply shocked by this catastrophe. So many people are
asking why this happened,'' Pflanz said. ``But there really is no
answer.''
   The service took place 1{ miles from the U.S. base, where the
disaster involving an Italian stunt-flying team occurred Sunday.
After three planes from the team collided, one fell into a crowd of
spectators and exploded.
   Hundreds of people stood in a light rain outside the small brick
church today before the German-American memorial service, which was
broadcast live on nationwide television.
   Several relatives of the dead, weeping and wringing their hands,
entered the church nearly an hour before the service started.
   Many Ramstein residents stood solemenly at their windows
watching the guests arrive. The skies over the town, usually filled
with military traffic headed towards Europe's largest military
base, were quiet.
   In addition to Weizsaecker, others attending the service were
U.S. Ambassador Richard Burt, base commander Gen. William Kirk and
Italian Defense Minister Valerio Zanone. Several relatives of the
victims also attended.
   ``Last Sunday, hundreds of thousands came to marvel at the
technology of flight and to admire those who have mastered it,''
Burt said.
   ``Sunday's tragedy has brought home to each of us the fragility
of life and made us recognize anew the limits to man's mastery of
his world.'' He added: ``We will ensure that such a tragedy is
never repeated.''
   The death toll climbed to 51 when Rhineland-Palatinate state
government spokesman Juergen Dietzen said two more West Germans
died. He said 165 people remained hospitalized and that more than
20 had life-threatening burns.
   Two Americans were among the dead _ a 9-year-old boy and his
mother. Air Force officials have identified them as Joshua Frymyer
and his mother, 36-year-old Army Pfc. Genevieve Riggs, who were
stationed in West Germany.
   Mrs. Riggs' husband, Army Sgt. Myron Riggs, was among the seven
people evacuated to the United States for treatment of burns. Ms.
White said the bodies of the mother and son were flown back to the
United States.
</TEXT>
