<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 1047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PalestinianPlans Bjt   09-03 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palestinian Plans, Bjt,0867</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Debate On Future Causes Friction Among Palestinians</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Throughout the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, Palestinians are holding an intense and sometimes
violent debate on the wisdom of declaring a state and forming a
provisional government.
   Leading members of Yasser Arafat's Fatah faction of the
Palestine Liberation Organization have proposed recognizing Israel
and seeking international recognition for statehood on the West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   These ideas are meeting surprisingly strong opposition from
Islamic groups and radical leftists.
   The misgivings prompted a recent decision to postpone until the
first week of October a meeting of the 447-seat Palestine National
Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile.
   The debate also has touched off some inter-Palestinian violence.
Last month, for example, the car of a prominent Islamic
fundamentalist was firebombed in Gaza and PLO supporters were
blamed.
   Daoud Kuttab, a prominent journalist and leading advocate of the
provisional government idea, wrote in the weekly Al Sinara that
Palestinians ``should not hesitate'' or they would lose a golden
opportunity.
   ``One of the problems in the past has been that the PLO was too
tied to the principle of national consensus. You can't have total
agreement on every issue. The majority should decide. Having some
opposition, in fact, would be healthy,'' Kuttab said in an
interview.
   Kuttab argued a major benefit of changing from a guerrilla
organization to a provisional government would be an improvement of
the Palestinian image, especially in Western eyes.
   ``Instead of guerrilla fatigues, Arafat will be wearing a suit
and tie. It's a good idea to change the image of Palestinians as
revolutionaries, which is looked at negatively in the West,'' he
said.
   Kuttab said a provisional government also would have more
flexibility in negotiations and be able to change positions when
necessary in contrast with the PLO, which had to cling to
revolutionary ideals.
   Moslem fundamentalists of the Islamic Jihad (Holy War) and the
even harder line Hamas (Zeal) are opposed to the existence of a
Jewish state. They demand an Islamic state and remain outside the
PLO because it calls for a secular nation.
   ``I don't think it's the right time to establish a provisional
government or declare an independent state because the Palestinian
side is weak, and the weak are always commanded by the strong,''
said Ahmed Ismail Yassin, spiritual leader of the Islamic Jihad.
   Yassin, who is paralyzed and confined to a wheelchair, is a
charismatic figure who preaches in the Mujamaa Islami Mosque on a
dirt street in the run-down Sabra section of Gaza City. He was
released in a prisoner exchange in 1985 after being sentenced to 13
years in jail for financing Islamic militants.
   In an interview, Yassin said, ``If the PLO doesn't change some
of its ideas, there is no need for us to cooperate with them.''
   Yassin, who has hinted that fundamentalists may form an
alternative PLO if a secular state is declared, indicated he was
concerned about inter-Palestinian violence and warned it was a
``dangerous disease.''
   The Islamic militants broke off cooperation last spring with the
clandestine United National Leadership of the Uprising, which is
believed to be made up of representatives from the PLO factions.
   Both groups issue separate underground leaflets calling for
competing strikes and boycotts. They also proclaim their positions
in multi-colored graffiti that covers walls and shops throughout
the occupied lands.
   The slogans of the Islamic militants usually have a religious
theme: ``Our martyrs are in heaven, yours are in hell.''
   Criticism of Fatah's campaign also comes from the left.
   ``They (Fatah) are forcing the issue on which there is no
unanimity,'' said Haidar Abdel Shaafi, a prominent figure
associated with the Communists.
   Abdel Shafi, head of the Palestinian Red Crescent society, the
Moslem equivalent of the Red Cross, said he opposed for tactical
reasons making the concession of recognizing Israel in advance of
negotiations.
   ``The matter of recognizing the Jewish presence here is really
no longer in question. But how can I recognize Israel when Israel
does not recongize me, when Israel claims all of Palestinian to be
their territory,'' Abdel Shafi said.
   He said he hoped the Palestinian council would not take a
decison until after Israel's Nov. 1 elections so as to not to make
advance concessions.
   It is not known which group commands the most support, although
the conventional wisdom is that Islamic militants have the backing
of most of Gaza's 650,000 residents and Fatah controls most of the
West Bank's 850,000 Palestinians.
   Israel's Foreign Ministry has set up a special unit to monitor
the statements of prominent Palestinians on the issue, according to
sources who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``We are closely monitoring it. But it has com to the point
where we are taking seriously only decisions, not declarations,''
said one Foreign Ministry official.
   ``They always surprise us with their inability to decide, but
they are making a big mistake this time,'' he said. ``They are
going to disappoint people in the (occupied) territories.''
</TEXT>
