<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ToxicCloud 1stLd-Writethru a0516 09-03 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Toxic Cloud, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0516,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chlorine Leak Forces Evacuation of 20,000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout to CORRECT with gas identified as
chlorine, evacuation up to 20,000, unknown if leak has been
stopped. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT JABLON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COMMERCE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leak of chlorine gas from an
industrial plant forced the evacuation today of an estimated 20,000
people east of Los Angeles, and seven people were taken to
hospitals, officials said.
   The chemical cloud, measuring more than a half-mile long, formed
early this morning, said Los Angeles County Sheriff's Deputy Dan
Cox.
   Firefighters and sheriff's deputies evacuated 20,000 from
surrounding neighborhoods, about 10 miles east of downtown Los
Angeles, said Deputy Van Mosley. Wind was light and variable,
according to the National Weather Service.
   Wispy, smoky-gray fumes poured from the Grow Group Inc. plant,
which makes chlorine tablets for swimming pools, said Kim Marti,
plant manager.
   It was not immediately known if the leak had been stopped by
morning.
   Marti said a chemical reaction produced the chlorine, which can
be lethal in high concentrations but otherwise causes burning eyes
and sore throats.
   ``Until we get in there and identify what caused the reaction, I
can't tell you. I don't know,'' Marti said.
   The manager said the the plant was closed at the time of the
incident, which was reported to county officials at 12:19 a.m.
``The sheriff's department woke us up,'' Marti said.
   Three people were in stable condition at Santa Marta Hospital
and Clinic, said nursing supervisor Verna Brinson.
   Four others with respiratory complaints were treated at
County-USC Medical Center and released, said Norka Manning, a
hospital spokeswoman.
   Firefighters sent a hazardous materials unit, which requested
soda ash to stabilize the chemical, said Hubert Parker, a spokesman
for the county Fire Department.
   The area evacuated comprised several square miles in portions of
East Los Angeles, Monterey Park, Montebello and Commerce,
authorities said.
   ``We're evacuating the whole southern end of our city,'' said
Monterey Park police Officer Frank Valiente. ``We don't know when
we're going to allow them to come back.''
   Residents were sent to several high schools where the Red Cross
had set up emergency shelters.
   As the huge cloud began drifting to the southwest, it threatened
to close Interstate 5, one of the busiest freeways in Southern
California. The California Highway Patrol closed an exit ramp along
the freeway, the southern boundary of the evacuated area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
