<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 1143EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Booze-Presidents     09-03 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Booze-Presidents,200</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 12:01 a.m. EDT Sunday, time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Children Recognize More Beverages than Presidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's past presidents may need more
advertising, judging from a survey that found youngsters able to
name more brands of alcoholic beverages than former chief
executives.
   The children, ages 8 to 12, were each able to name an average of
5.2 alcoholic beverages, but just 4.8 presidents, reported the
Center for Science in the Public Interest.
   The Center, a non-profit health advocacy group, said it surveyed
180 boys and girls in Washington, D.C., and suburban Maryland.
   ``This survey indicates the extent to which booze is part of the
daily life of children who cannot drink legally for another 10
years,'' commented Michael Jacobson, head of the Center.
   Among the findings of the survey:
   _A 10-year-old girl rattled off 14 alcoholic beverages but could
name only four presidents.
   _An 11-year-old boy, who could name eight brands of beer and
wine, said there are 16 inches in a foot.
   _Another 11-year-old boy correctly spelled Matilda Bay, King
Cobra and Bud Light, but rendered the presidents' names as
``Nickson'' and ``Rosselvet.''
   _And a 7-year-old boy who could name 10 brands of beer and wine
listed as presidents ``Aprilham Linchon'' and ``Ragon.''
</TEXT>
