<1ST_LINE>u a AM-StarkReturn     09-03 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stark Return,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USS Stark Returns Home To Mayport</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The USS Stark returned to a
low-key welcome at its home port Saturday after 10 months in a
shipyard to repair $90 million damage caused by two Iraqi missiles
in the Persian Gulf.
   About 100 people were on hand as the guided-missile frigate
docked at Bravo pier, where a memorial to the 37 sailors killed in
the May 1987 attack has been placed.
   It is the same pier from which the Stark left in February 1987
for what was to have been routine duty in the Persian Gulf.
   ``It's good to be a family again instead of a long-distance
family,'' said Jennifer Hayward, who with her three children waited
for her husband.
   She recalled how the crippled ship was greeted by hundreds of
people bearing balloons and welcome-home banners when it returned
after the attack last year. ``Last August, it was a a lot more
emotional,'' she said.
   Lt. Cmdr. Tim Taylor, a Navy spokesman, said that no ceremony
was scheduled for the return of the Stark from Ingalls Shipbuilding
in Pascagoula, Miss., where it underwent repairs.
   ``We want the Stark to be just like every other ship,'' said
Mayport's commanding officer, Capt. John Mitchell.
   Another ship, the USS Boone, also came home Saturday after a
one-year overhaul in New Orleans. ``It's no different, one from the
other,'' Mitchell said.
   The Stark left Mississippi on Wednesday with 16 officers and 174
enlisted men who spent the year in Mississippi helping with the
repairs or doing other Navy work.
   Before heading home, the ship passed trials of its guns, its
ability to track air and surface targets, its engines and its
steering. The repairs were completed on time and cost about $52
million less than estimated, officials said.
   The searing heat from the Exocet missiles destroyed the Stark's
berthing area and combat information center as well as radar
equipment rooms and other compartments.
   The Stark underwent temporary repairs in Bahrain after the
attack before the long voyage home a year ago.
   The government of Iraq, which claimed responsibility for the
attack, will be sent a bill for the repair costs. It also has
promised to compensate the families of the 37 sailors killed in
what it said was an accidental attack.
</TEXT>
