<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 1209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MarsMonth     09-03 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mars Month,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mars at Closest to Earth in 17 Years This Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mars will move to within about 36 million miles
of Earth this month _ the closest its been in 17 years _ and dozens
of ``Mars watches'' are planned to view the red planet named for
the Roman god of war.
   The planet will come closest to Earth on Sept. 22, but the best
time to see it is the next few nights, said Norman Warns, an
astronomy professor at South Suburban College in South Holland, a
Chicago suburb.
   ``It's a perfect time to see because the moon doesn't come up
until late at night,'' Warns said Friday. ``It's a definite orange
bright spot in the southeastern sky at about 10 at night.''
   The Planetary Society, an amateur astronomy group, plans about
50 Mars watches this month, said Linda Low, the group's Illinois
regional coordinator. Thousands of smaller, informal Mars parties
also will be held, she said.
   On Saturday, outer-space buffs were encouraged to bring Mars
bars and other earthly delights to a Mars watch, picnic and jazz
concert at the college.
   The last time Earth and Mars were so close was in 1971, Warns
said. He said viewing conditions this time are better because the
planet is much higher in the sky.
   ``It'll appear the brightest during September. Then it'll get
dimmer as the two planets move away,'' he said.
   Warns said that unless Mars watchers look at the planet through
a high-powered telescope, ``it might look to some people like a
star.''
   ``You won't see any Martians no matter what size telescope you
have, but the larger the telescope you have, the more you'll see,''
he said.
   ``You actually need a small telescope to see a disc ... and with
a medium-size telescope you can actually see surface features,''
Warns said. ``Under favorable conditions you would even see a white
spot which marks the polar ice cap.''
   Observers also should be on the lookout for dark spots, massive
dust storms on the planet, he said.
   With a very powerful telescope, they might also see the Valley
of the Mariner, a five-mile-deep, twenty-mile-wide canyon that
would stretch from New York to Los Angeles if it were on Earth.
   Astrologer Del O'Connor said even those who pay no attention to
Mars will be affected by it.
   She warned that people should be more careful and not make any
rash decisions because of the unusual influence this month of the
planet said by astrologers to have high energy.
   ``Whatever is going on during this period will happen with
greater intensity because Mars as a planet represents raw energy,''
Ms. O'Connor said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
