<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MisidentifiedConvict     09-03 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Misidentified Convict,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Convicts for Murder Despite Witnesses' Misidentification</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Miron is cq in 2nd graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was convicted of murder despite the
testimony of two witnesses who identified the interpreter sitting
beside him as the killer.
   Jurors deliberated less than 20 minutes Thursday before
convicting Mariano Medina, 45, in the 1986 slaying of Pablo
Rodriguez. Judge Miron Love sentenced Medina to 20 years in prison.
   Two elderly witnesses had pointed to court interpreter Sammy
Garcia as the man they saw gun down Rodriguez.
   Garcia, who was seated beside Medina through the trial, said the
misidentification reminded him of ``something you see on `Perry
Mason.'''
   Mike Roe, the assistant district attorney, had stressed in final
arguments that the witnesses did identify Medina in a photo lineup
shortly after the slaying. ``Don't reward him for changing his
appearance,'' he told the jurors.
   Roe said that in the past two years, Medina has lost 20 pounds,
grown a mustache and put on glasses. Both Medina and Garcia have
dark complexions and dark, wavy hair.
   One of the witnesses had provided police with the license number
of the car driven by Rodriguez's assailant, leading authorities to
Medina. One of Medina's neighbors also testified she saw him load a
revolver shortly before hearing shots nearby.
   Prosecutors argued that Medina shot Rodriguez because he
suspected him of burglarizing his apartment.
</TEXT>
