<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 1242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     09-03 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Representative To Meet With Burma President, Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Stephen J. Solarz said Saturday
he would meet with government and opposition leaders to see how the
United States can encourage democracy after 26 years of
authoritarian rule.
   Small groups of anti-government protesters met in the capital,
but there were no rallies after a week of major demonstrations
against the one-party rule of the Burma Socialist Program Party.
   ``I've come in order to assess the situation and its
implications for American interest in the region,'' Solarz said
after arriving Saturday in Rangoon. He was reached by telephone
from Bangkok, Thailand.
   Solarz said he wanted to ``see what, if anything, the United
States can do to facilitate the peaceful emergence of a genuine
democracy.''
   Sources said Solarz would meet separately with President Maung
Maung; with Aung Gyi, Burma's best-known dissident, who was
recently freed from a month's detention; and with Tin Oo, a former
defense minister who re-emerged to lead calls for multi-party
democracy.
   Solarz, D-N.Y., chairs the Asian and Pacific Affairs
Subcommittee of the House Foreign Affairs Committee. He has spoken
out against against repressive policies of former Philippine
President Ferdinand Marcos and the ultra-radical Khmer Rouge that
ruled Cambodia until 1978.
   Diplomats say the international community has limited influence
over Burma because it is a strictly neutralist nation without close
allies. Burma also is extremely sensitive to what it considers to
be foreign interference.
   Japan and West Germany are the biggest aid donors. The United
States has a relatively modest aerial spraying program aimed
largely at helping Rangoon combat opium production in the so-called
``Golden Triangle.''
   Hundreds of thousands of people marched through major cities
Friday, demanding immediate democracy and rejecting Maung Maung's
appeal to be patient in their quest.
   Students and other protest leaders called for large-scale
demonstrations on Sept. 8 to press for an interim government to
oversee the transition to democracy. Strikes and protests have been
virtually daily events.
   The government has not backed down from its original plan for
party leaders to meet Sept. 12 to consider calling for a popular
vote on ending one-party rule. The protesters want an interim
government formed before then, but Maung Maung has rejected that
for constitutional reasons.
   Burma has been under single-party rule since Gen. Ne Win led the
1962 military coup that toppled an elected government.
   Ne Win resigned on July 23 and proposed a referendum on ending
one-party rule. But the party rejected that and picked hard-liner
Sein Lwin to succeed him.
   Massive protests followed, and by official count at least 112
people were killed in clashes with security forces in Rangoon
before Sein Lwin resigned Aug. 12.
   Maung Maung, the first civilian leader in 26 years, succeeded
him a week later, lifted martial law and freed political prisoners.
But pro-democracy demonstrations continued and a general strike has
crippled government services and administration in many areas.
   On Friday, a Western diplomat in Rangoon cited reports that
protesters have taken over about 40 town governments in recent
weeks.
   Another indication of the breakdown in order has been several
jail riots, after which authorities freed thousands of inmates.
State-run Radio Rangoon said 486 prisoners were freed Saturday in
the central city of Mandalay.
</TEXT>
