<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 1254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile-Pinochet 1stLd-Writethru a0544 09-03 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Pinochet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0544,0761</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Seizes Initiative In Campaign To Rule Eight More Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 8 to CORRECT spelling of Arriagada, RECASTS graf 14
to clarify. Picks up graf 15 pvs, `It also ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet has seized the
initiative in a carefully orchestrated campaign for eight more
years of military rule, extending highly publicized olive branches
to critics of his authoritarian government.
   But the Chilean opposition remains confident of defeating the
72-year-old army commander at the voting booth in a presidential
plebiscite scheduled for Oct. 5.
   In two adept moves, made 48 hours after fellow military
commanders nominated him Tuesday as sole candidate in a
presidential referendum, Pinochet broadcast a conciliatory appeal
for opposition collaboration and authorized the return of all 430
remaining political exiles.
   Leaders of the local Roman Catholic Church lauded both measures
as helping national reconciliation. ``We have to be truly happy
with these positive steps,'' said the country's cardinal, Juan
Francisco Fresno.
   It was rare praise from the church hierarchy, which has been
consistently critical of Pinochet since he seized power in a bloody
1973 coup. The church's pronouncements carry much weight with
Chile's predominantly Catholic population.
   Coupled with the lifting last month of all states of emergency
for the first time since Pinochet took power, even the opposition
leaders said Chile was moving toward greater political freedom.
   They denounced the timing of the actions, however, as a cynical
bid for publicity and voter support, and they predicted this could
backfire for the government.
   ``It creates a greater sense of security in the country,'' said
Genaro Arriagada, general secretary of a 16-party opposition
coalition. This could make many Pinochet opponents feel safe from
reprisal if they vote against him in the referendum, Arriagada said.
   The opposition's campaign, which consists largely of festive
rallies and door-to-door visits, is focused heavily on overcoming
fears that citizens might lose government jobs or benefits, such as
housing subsidies, if they vote ``no.''
   A campaign slogan, used extensively by opposition leaders in
rallies, is ``say yes, but vote no.''
   If Pinochet wins a majority in the referendum, he begins a new
eight-year term in March. He already has governed the country
longer than any predecessor.
   Even if a majority of voters rejects him, he will remain
president until 1990, when open elections will be held. Elections
for Congress, disbanded by Pinochet when he seized power, are
planned for the same year.
   Pinochet trails badly in many polls, including those that
foreign diplomats describe as the most reliable. His new attempts
at the image of peacemaker appear aimed at making headway with the
many Chileans offended by his harsh, strong-arm image.
   Pinochet rejects the poll indications, favoring pro-government
surveys that give him a slight edge. But even if he were to
conclude that the opposition held a commanding lead it now appears
too late to back out and, for instance, call open elections that
might split the opposition.
   It also appears too late for the opposition, despite its
complaints that the government enjoys an unfair advantage, to
withdraw from the competition.
   ``This (referendum) is a path from which it would be difficult
for Pinochet to stray,'' Arriagada said. ``And, to be honest, from
which it would be difficult for us to stray, either.''
   The opposition maintains that Pinochet is spending millions of
dollars in public money on pro-government publicity and providing
logistical support, such as municipal stadiums free of charge, to
political groups campaigning for him.
   The pro-Pinochet campaign's central message is that a loss in
the referendum would bring back social and political chaos of the
early 1970s, when an elected Marxist, Salvador Allende, was
president. Allende's government was toppled, and he died, in the
1973 coup.
   A major anti-Pinochet rally was planned for Sunday in Santiago,
and organizers say they are doing their best to make sure it and
future demonstrations are peaceful, designating chaperones to keep
order and control any rowdy groups.
   ``Any violence helps Pinochet,'' said Patricio Aylwin, leader of
the centrist Christian Democratic Party, the country's largest, and
official spokesman for the opposition coalition. ``We must do all
we can to prevent it.''
   Aylwin tried to take the campaign initiative Thursday by
challenging Pinochet to a televised debate. It was considered
unlikely the president would agree.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Kevin Noblet is The Associated Press' bureau
chief in Santiago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
