<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan-Economy     09-03 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Economy,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Threatens Veto Of Welfare Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today he will
veto any welfare bill sent him by Congress that ``replaces work
with welfare expansion.''
   In his weekly radio address, delivered from his mountaintop
ranch north of here, the president said the economic expansion
under his administration has enabled nearly three million Americans
to escape poverty.
   ``But this week we got a warning,'' he added. ``While we learned
that last year family income went up and that the poverty rate
dropped slightly, we also learned that some groups lagged behind in
the last year.''
   ``There are still some Americans whom our expansion has passed
by: those caught in the welfare trap,'' he said.
   ``It's time to return hope to those on welfare, which is why our
administration has worked to reform our welfare system,'' the
president said.
   He said nearly half of the 50 states have either instituted or
proposed experimental welfare plans under an administration program
designed to foster steps to get people off welfare.
   ``Now, Congress appears to be close to a decision about welfare
reform,'' he added. ``And I have a message for them: I will not
accept any welfare reform bill unless it is geared to making people
independent of welfare.
   ``If Congress presents me with a bill that replaced work with
welfare expansion and that places the dignity of self-sufficiency
through work out of the reach of Americans on welfare, I will use
my veto pen,'' he said.
   The Senate has passed a bill that does contain a work
requirement, but the measure passed by the House does not. The two
bills are being considered by a House-Senate conference committee.
   ``While others have talked about good jobs at good wages, we've
delivered,'' the president said. ``Now it is time for Congress to
join with us in making sure that the opportunities created by this
prosperity reach into every American home.''
   The president began his speech by saying that ``just yesterday
we learned that in August as great a proportion of us had jobs as
ever before.''
   The Labor Department reported Friday that unemployment rose to
5.6 percent in August from 5.4 percent in July. In May,
unemployment had reached a 14-year low of 5.3 percent.
</TEXT>
