<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NorthernIreland 4thLd-Writethru a0554 09-03 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0554,0791</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>IRA Killer Allowed Out Of Prison To Attend Brother's Funeral</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throut to UPDATE with Mullin allowed out of prison to
attend brother's funeral, mortar attack on military base. TRIMS. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUNMOYLE, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today released
a convicted Irish Republican Army killer to attend the funeral of
his brother, an IRA guerrilla who was slain in a British army
ambush.
   Across the province in Londonderry, family and friends buried
two people who were killed by an IRA bomb, and Roman Catholic
Bishop Edward Daly said he did not ``want to hear any more
apologies from the IRA or anyone else.''
   In Crossmaglen, meanwhile, a town near the border with Ireland,
a mortar attack on a military base damaged some nearby buildings
but caused no injuries. Police said three mortars exploded and that
other shells failed to exploded.
   Earlier today, hundreds of police and soldiers in riot gear
formed an almost unbroken circle around the home of slain IRA
guerrilla Brian Mullin at Sixmilecross, 50 miles west of Belfast
before his funeral.
   Mullin's elder brother Patrick, serving a life sentence for the
IRA murder of a school bus driver, was given a day's compassionate
leave to attend the funeral and was released in the custody of a
local priest and driven from Maze prison in Belfast by members of
Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing.
   Patrick Mullin was delayed at a security checkpoint, and the
cortege of 2,000 mourners did not leave the farm at Sixmilecross
for nearby Dunmoyle until about noon, one hour later than scheduled.
   A previous report said the delay occurred because family members
demanded the security forces leave the vicinity of the house before
they would come out.
   More than 200 police and soldiers later accompanied the hearse
carrying Mullin's coffin which was draped with the Irish tricolor
flag.
   Mullin was killed along with two other men in an ambush by
British soldiers. Police say Mullin, 26, and brothers Gerard Harte,
29, and Martin Harte, 21, were known IRA members who were armed and
masked when they were killed at Drumnakilly 50 miles west of
Belfast on Tuesday.
   News reports said the three guerrillas were about to try to kill
an off-duty member of the Ulster Defense Regiment when soldiers
lying in wait riddled their stolen car with bullets. The IRA said
the three men died ``on active service,'' a euphemism for gun and
bomb attacks.
   The Harte brothers were buried Friday, and Mullin's funeral was
scheduled for today before the standoff began between security
forces and his family.
   In Londonderry, Bishop Daly presided at the funeral of Sean
Dalton 55, and Sheila Lewis, 60, who were killed by a booby-trap
bomb Wednesday when they went to examine the apartment of a
neighbor they had not seen in several days.
   Dalton broke into the apartment and triggered a bomb rigged to
blow up an army squad. The IRA apologized, saying the operation
went ``tragically wrong.''
   Daly told the congregation he wanted to hear no more apologies.
   Before the Mullin funeral, Protestant lawmaker Ken Maginnis said
Patrick was going to be let out of prison to attend the funeral.
   Maginnis, a member of the Protestant Official Unionist Party,
said the British government's Northern Ireland Office told him it
would allow Mullin's brother to attend the funeral. The office, the
British government department responsible for the province's
affairs, refused to comment.
   Patrick Mullin is serving a life term for the 1977 killing of
Roman Catholic bus driver Frank Canavan. The IRA said at the time
that Canavan was mistaken for a part-time member of the Ulster
Defense Regiment, a locally recruited unit of the British army.
   The mainly Catholic IRA, which is fighting to end British rule
in Northern Ireland, apologized for what it called Canavan's
``tragic death.''
   ``It is an absolute scandal that this man (Patrick Mullin), who
is one of a committed IRA family, should be released, or paroled or
whatever it is called,'' Maginnis said. ``The concession for the
funeral of a terrorist involved in the murder of eight young
soldiers exactly 14 days ago is a concession to IRA terrorism quite
beyond comprehension.''
   Police arrested Brian Mullin after an IRA bomb blew up a
military bus on Aug. 20, killing eight soldiers and injuring 27
others. He was questioned and released after five days without
being charged.
   The bombing occurred at Ballygawley, eight miles from where
Mullin and the Hartes were killed. ``We know he (Mullin) was in the
same (IRA) unit that carried out the (bus) bombing,'' Maginnis said.
</TEXT>
