<DOCNO> AP880903-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 1347EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Kurds     09-03 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Kurds,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>90,000 Kurds Huddled Along Border After Fleeing Iraq</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VEDAT ERDAMAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CUKURCA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 90,000 Kurdish refugees, many sick
and exhausted, have fled fighting in Iraq and resettled with
bedding and household utensils under trees in Turkish camps.
   They are huddled along small, tree-lined creeks with their sheep
and goats grazing nearby in eight encampments along a 60-mile strip
near the Iraqi border.
   Many children and old people are suffering from exhaustion and
diarrhea, said doctors screening the refugees Saturday.
   Next week, Turkey will start moving the refugees about 60 miles
inland to tent cities being set up north of the Syrian border in
Diyarbakir province and near the Cizre and Silopi townships, local
officials said Saturday.
   Thirty trucks to be used in the move have been sent to a camp
near Cukurca, known as Cukurca Yayla, where 11,000 refugees have
taken shelter, said town Mayor Macit Piruzbeyoglu.
   The doctors, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said 18 people
died in the Cukurca Yayla camp on Friday. They did not appear to be
victims of chemical bombs, the doctors said, but relatives would
not allow autopsies so it was not possible to know for sure.
   Kurds in northern Iraq have been fighting for an independent
homeland and received help from Iran during the eight-year
Iran-Iraq war. Soon after the warring nations agreed to a
cease-fire on Aug. 20, Iraq launched an offensive against the
Kurdish guerrillas, known as Peshmergas.
   About 20 million Kurds live in the mountains where the borders
of Turkey, Iran and Iraq meet, and Syria and the Soviet Union also
have small Kurdish enclaves. About 3.5 million Kurds live in Iraq.
   The Iraqi refugees say they fled when Iraqis dropped mustard gas
bombs, outlawed under international accords.
   Serbest Omar, 25, carrying a gas mask, said, ``On the way over,
I personally buried 15 dead from our group.
   ``Some died from hunger and illness and others from chemical
bombs,'' he said.
   He said only 800 of the 1300 residents of Tirvanish, his village
in the Dohuk township of northern Iraq, had survived.
   Amnesty International has backed up the Kurdish charges, saying
Iraqis have used chemical weapons against them in a campaign of
extermination.
   Iraq has denied using chemical weapons against the Kurds, though
it has said it was provoked to use them against Iran after Iran
used them first. Iraq considers the refugees traitors who
collaborated with Iran during the war.
   Ahmed Mohammed, 35, from another village in Dohuk township, said
refugees waited four days while the Iraqi army blocked their way.
They slipped through the blockade at night and then walked six days
to the Turkish border, he said.
   His mother and father died en route, he said.
   The refugees in the Cukurca Yayla camp have separated into
groups of nine or 10 people, each group taking shelter under a tree.
   Women make flat bread from flour distributed by the Turkish
government and brew tea. Some of the refugees cut down tree
branches to make hammocks and rock little children to sleep on them.
   Turkey announced Wednesday it would accept the refugees
temporarily on humanitarian grounds. The refugees and local
officials say the influx started earlier.
   ``They started coming in the middle of August,'' said Mayor
Piruzbeyoglu. He said groups of refugees had previously crossed
into Turkey in 1962 and 1975, during heavy fighting between the
Iraqi army and the Kurds, but he said the numbers were much smaller
then.
   Turkey hesitated to accept the refugees because its military is
fighting its own battle in southeastern Turkey with guerrillas
known as the Kurdish Labor Party.
   The rebels, who want to set up an independent, Marxist Kurdish
state, are not popular with the 10 million Kurdish residents of the
region. The guerrillas have slain several hundred villagers whom
they accused of cooperating with government forces.
   Since 1984, about 700 troops and 700 guerrillas have died in the
struggle.
   Premier Turgut Ozal's decision to give refuge to the Iraqi Kurds
has boosted his popularity among Kurdish residents in the
southeast, many of whom have relatives among the refugees, local
politicians say.
   This could serve him well in a Sept. 25 referendum on a
constitutional amendment to move up the date of municipal elections.
   Officials also hope the move will improve Turkey's image in the
West. Ozal has said Turkey's refugee policy is the best answer to
criticism of this country's human rights record or its treatment of
the Kurdish minority.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880903-0091 </DOCNO>
