<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BracesCookbook     09-03 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Braces Cookbook,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Pens Cookbook For Braces-Wearers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jennifer McJunkin put up with three years
of struggling with food stuck between her braces and knew just what
she needed on her menu: Practically Chewless Chili and Tin Grin
Torte.
   Those recipes and many others went into Ms. McJunkin's ``Teen
Cuisine: A Cookbook for Young People Who Wear Orthodontic Braces.''
   ``Orthodontists always tell you what you can't eat but they
never tell you what you can, and that's what we're trying to do
here,'' said Ms. McJunkin, now 20 and a junior at Drew University
here.
   Ms. McJunkin isn't the first one in her family to do battle with
braces, nor the first one to cook up a solution. Her parents
published a cookbook for adults with braces after her mother wore
them for several years.
   ``A lot of foods are so hard to eat because they're crunchy and
hard,'' Ms. McJunkin said. ``A lot of things get stuck in your
teeth, like salad and corn. These are alternatives to those.''
   The cookbook also is designed to help wearers avoid food that
bend their braces or pulls the hardware from their mouths. It
emphasizes soft foods such as pasta, and some recipes rely on
chopped, pureed or softened ingredients.
   In addition to the chili and torte, the 66-page book lists such
gourmet choices as Painless Pizza Soup and Metal Mouth Munchies, a
``mild and gentle'' snack of Chex cereal softened with margarine
and teriyaki or Worcestershire sauce.
   Most of the recipes came from her family, including Aunt
Geneva's Foolproof Fudge, Cousin Derek's Cereal Sundae and
Jennifer's Favorite Lemon Bars.
   Ms. McJunkin said she spent 2{ years testing the recipes on
every braces-wearing person she knew.
   Ms. McJunkin was a fifth-grader when she got braces to correct
an overbite and a gap between two front teeth. Even worse, her
family had just moved to Indiana.
   ``It was awful to be the new girl and to have braces,'' she
said. ``I really felt I kind of stuck out in the crowd. I told my
mother that I'd never smile again.''
   The McJunkins discussed the cookbook idea with the family's
orthodontist, who offered the manuscript to Straight Status Inc. of
New Castle, Ind., which produces greeting cards, stationery and
novelty items for orthodontists, dentists and their patients.
   The cookbook came off the press in January. It is being
distributed by the mail order company and may soon be available in
hospital gift shops and book stores.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
