<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 1402EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-LePen     09-03 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Le Pen,0714</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Minister Seeks Charges Against Rightist Leader For Pun</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The justice minister asked a local prosecutor
Saturday to file charges against extreme-right leader Jean-Marie Le
Pen for making a play on words linking a Cabinet minister's name to
Nazi death camp ovens.
   Le Pen refused to apologize for his remark, saying it was up to
others to judge if the pun was ``in good taste or not.''
   Justice Minister Pierre Arpaillange said Le Pen should be
prosecuted under an 1881 law that makes it a criminal offense to
insult a Cabinet minister, a ministry statement said.
   Local prosecutors work under the Justice Ministry's direction,
and while the minister does not have authority to order a
prosecution his wishes are unlikely to be disregarded.
   Le Pen's reference to Michel Durafour, minister for the public
service in the government of Socialist Premier Michel Rocard, as
``Durafour-crematoire'' brought criticism and revulsion from
politicians, Jewish organizations and civil rights groups.
   ``Four'' is the French word for oven, and the crematoriums of
Nazi death camps are called ``fours-crematoires'' in French.
   Durafour said he had ``an infinite amount of contempt'' for Le
Pen, leader of the extreme-right National Front, who won 14 percent
of the vote in presidential elections April 24.
   ``I can see he regrets the passing of the good old days of the
Nazis, and wishes he could see them come again,'' Durafour said.
   Le Pen replied at a news conference, ``In that case, Mr.
Durafour is not just an imbecile but a dirty bum as well.''
   As for his pun, Le Pen said, ``Everyone can judge for himself
whether it was in good taste or not. It's not my problem.''
   Le Pen, who had fallen out of the political spotlight in recent
months, got the attention back Friday in a speech to a National
Front rally. He made repeated sarcastic references to Durafour, a
centrist who served as a Cabinet minister in conservative
governments in the 1970s.
   Durafour has said he decided to accept a post in Rocard's
Socialist-led government in part because of the rising influence of
the National Front on the right. He has been outspoken in calling
for all other political parties to refuse electoral alliances with
Le Pen.
   The anti-racism group SOS-Racism issued a statement saying Le
Pen ``continues to blow on the flames of antisemitism in our
country.''
   Henri Bulawko, vice president of the Representative Council of
Jewish Organizations of France, said Le Pen, ``carried away by his
fantasies, did not hesitate to insult the memory of the victims of
Nazism.''
   Politicians from the right and the left joined in blasting Le
Pen's remark.
   ``There are things one cannot let go. There are words with which
one does not make jokes,'' said Alain Juppe, secretary-general of
the conservative Rally for the Republic Party.
   ``Mr. Le Pen is showing what he is at heart: a racist and an
antisemite,'' said Jean-Jack Queyranne, spokesman for the Socialist
Party.
   The leftist newspaper Liberation and the rightist Le Figaro used
identical front-page headlines Saturday: ``Le Pen Does It Again.''
   Last year, Le Pen drew harsh criticism for calling the Nazi gas
chambers ``a detail of World War II history.'' He is often accused
of being racist and antisemitic, but denies the charges, saying he
is simply pro-French.
   Le Pen's voting strength poses a delicate problem for the
rightist and centrist parties, especially in municipal elections
next spring.
   Control of dozens of cities and regional councils could depend
on whether the National Front supports center-right candidates or
opposes them. If the National Front splits the traditional rightist
vote, the Socialists and Communists could win large numbers of city
council posts and mayoral races.
   National Front leaders have been calling for an open alliance
with the right.
   But many conservative leaders say their parties will do better
if they ignore Le Pen and hope his backers come around, while
others support making local tactical pacts with the National Front
to keep the left out of power.
   Leftist leaders have urged the traditional right to make a clean
break with Le Pen.
</TEXT>
