<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Niger-Rain     09-03 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Niger-Rain,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thirteen Dead, 7,000 Homeless After Heavy Rains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NIAMEY, Niger (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flooding caused by the heaviest rains in
two decades have left 13 people dead and 7,000 homeless, the
minister of animal and water resources said Saturday.
   Boukar Ousmane, giving reporters an estimate of damage from
rains that have drenched most of the Sahel, also said more than 610
miles of roads were impassable and that the flooding washed out an
unknown number of bridges.
   He said the water covered about 250,000 acres of land and killed
at least 15,000 animals, including goats, cattle and sheep.
   But the heavy rains raised the Niger River to its highest levels
since record-keeping began in 1928 and promised to bring the best
harvests in 20 years. The rains continued Saturday morning in the
capital, Niamey.
   Officials were concerned, however, that portions of the crop
were threatened by a massive influx of crickets.
</TEXT>
