<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENWOOD, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Atlantic City Mayor Michael J.
Matthews changed prisons last week, and he did it all on his own.
   Matthews, who is serving a 15-year term for extortion, was
permitted to travel by himself Wednesday on a commercial flight
from Texas to Pennsylvania.
   No handcuffs, no shackles, no chaperones.
   After he arrived at the airport in Allenwood, Matthews took a
cab to the federal prison here.
   ``Two shocks in one day,'' the former mayor said Thursday night.
``First they told me I was going back, then they told me I was
going back on my own.''
   Matthews has been seeking a transfer to a prison closer to
Atlantic City since his 1984 sentencing.
   There was no answer at the warden's office Saturday and a
correctional officer said no one was available to comment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-songwriter Tracy Chapman, whose hit debut
album chronicles the lives of the poor and disenfranchised, says
many in her audiences don't come for her politics.
   ``I think lots of people come because they love the music, they
love the way the record sounds, or they love my voice, and they
don't care about any of the songs that have political content to
them,'' she said in the Sept. 22 issue of Rolling Stone.
   ``But for me it's just really important to know that people are
listening, and I think that for whatever reasons, they are.''
   Chapman, along with several other musicians, including Sting and
Bruce Springsteen, launched a six-week Amnesty International
concert tour Friday to promote human rights.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. William Proxmire hasn't missed a Senate
roll call since April 1966. That's more than 10,000 roll calls,
surpassing the record of 2,941 held by former Sen. Margaret Chase
Smith of Maine.
   ``You're elected to vote,'' the Wisconsin Democrat said. ``Of
course, some people would say the country would have been better
off if I'd missed them all.''
   Proxmire, who turns 73 in November, soon will see the streak
end. He announced last year he would retire when his term ends in
January.
   The senator has gained much of his fame for his monthly ``Golden
Fleece'' awards for government projects Proxmire considers wasteful.
   ``My primary role has been a watchdog over spending,'' said
Proxmire. ``I'd like to leave a legacy of people thinking about how
much things cost.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NORTH BAY VILLAGE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former screen siren Hedy Lamarr
has reported the theft of $250,000 in jewelry from her home here,
but police aren't hopping on the case.
   Detectives said the home showed no signs of a forced entry, and
they haven't received a list of the items taken.
   ``The last time she saw it was two or three months ago,''
Detective Frank DeAlimi said Friday of Ms. Lamarr's jewelry.
   He said the investigation is on hold until he receives a call
from Tiffany & Co. jewelry store in New York to confirm that the
74-year-old actress had the costly jewelry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music star Hank Williams Jr. has
more than a passing interest in his post as honorary chairman of
National Hunting and Fishing Day Sept. 24.
   He said he spends ``virtually every minute of my free time
hunting, shooting or tinkering with firearms.''
   Williams was on a hunting expedition in the Montana Rockies in
1975 when he fell 500 feet and was seriously hurt.
   His hits include ``Born to Boogie'' and ``All My Rowdy Friends
Are Comin' Over Tonight.''
