<1ST_LINE>r w AM-S&LTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0584 09-03 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&L Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0584,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Resolution in Talks to Save California Savings and Loan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT figure to 46 savings institutions,
sted 47</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators said Saturday that talks
with a Texas investment group on the rescue of American Savings and
Loan Association, Stockton, Calif., would continue through Monday.
   ``Discussions ... continue and a further announcement is planned
for Monday,'' said Karl Hoyle, spokesman for the Federal Home Loan
Bank Board.
   The regulators have been negotiating with the Robert M. Bass
Group of Fort Worth, Texas, over the rescue of the nation's largest
insolvent savings institution.
   According to industry sources, the proposal under discussion
involves a contribution of about $500 million from the Bass Group
and about $2 billion in assistance from the bank board, which would
make it the largest rescue ever of a single savings and loan.
   American is owned by Irvine, Calif.-based Financial Corp. of
America, the second-largest thrift holding company in the country
with $30.2 billion in assets as of June 30.
   Hoyle declined to characterize the discussions or identify the
issues that have been holding up resolution of the talks since
Thursday.
   The FCA rescue would be the latest in a series of large
transactions since mid-August cleaning up insolvent thrift
associations. Since Aug. 18, the bank board has committed $10.2
billion in aid to rescue 46 savings institutions, including 21 in
Texas and 14 in Oklahoma.
</TEXT>
