<DOCNO> AP880903-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 1435EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Eastern     09-03 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Spokesman Says They'll Eventually Win Case To Stop Layoffs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Machinists official said the union will fight a
federal appeals court ruling allowing Eastern Airlines to lay off
4,000 employees as soon as the money-losing carrier posts a $4.7
million bond.
   ``This is not the end of the world,'' Bob Taylor, head of
Eastern's Machinists local in Atlanta, said of the U.S. Court of
Appeals ruling Friday night. ``I still feel confident that we will
be proven right'' in a higher court.
   The court in Washington, D.C., granted Eastern's request to set
aside an injunction barring the layoffs, said Clark Onstad, a vice
president at Eastern's parent company, Texas Air Corp. of Houston.
   Eastern lawyer John J. Gallagher in Washington said it was
unclear when the carrier could post the amount and begin layoffs.
   Miami-based Eastern has lost about $1 billion in the past decade.
   It has been locked in battle with its unions to cut labor costs,
which the airline contends are responsible for its losses. The
Machinists are to vote Sept. 15 on a company proposal for $161
million in annual wage concessions.
   Unions contend Texas Air is cannibalizing Eastern in favor of
the company's non-union Continental Airlines.
   Eastern planned to layoff the workers and eliminate service to
14 cities last week to help return to profitability.
   The unions sued, and U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker ruled
Tuesday in Washington that Eastern could reduce its flight schedule
by 12 percent as planned but could not undertake mass layoffs
without negotiating with its unions.
   Eastern appealed, and its request was granted by Judges James L.
Buckley and Stephen F. Williams of the U.S. Court of Appeals.
   ``As we hoped, the Court of Appeals wasted no time in
overturning the order of the lower court, which we believed was
wrong as a matter of law,'' said Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak.
   Eastern contended a federal judge should not be able to restrict
management's ability to make cost-cutting moves it deems necessary.
   The layoffs had been scheduled to take effect Wednesday, when
the service was dropped. Employees in Kansas City, Mo.; Atlanta and
the metropolitan New York area were to be the most seriously
affected.
   Eastern eliminated its hub at Kansas City and sharply curtailed
service to the West. Remaining are its routes in the East, the
Caribbean and South America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
