<DOCNO> AP880903-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 1518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0590 09-03 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0590,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Defends Campaign Manager, Stumps Georgia and South Carolina</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT that Spencer lobbied for Noriega in
1985-86</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle
defended his campaign manager Saturday, saying he saw no reason for
him to step aside just because he had once lobbied for the
government of Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   At a news conference, Quayle gave his first detailed response to
revelations that his campaign manager, Stuart Spencer, had done
consulting work for the government run by Noriega. Quayle said
Spencer, a longtime GOP strategist and Reagan intimate, was ``a
political pro'' whose advice he needed.
   ``I believe that his political experience and political guidance
has been and will be valuable to me,'' Quayle said.
   The New Republic this week said that a public relations firm run
by Spencer was paid $350,000 in 1985-86 to lobby for Noriega,
Panama's military strongman and reputed drug kingpin.
   According to the article, the firm lobbied against drug
investigations of Noriega and defended him against allegations of
killing Dr. Hugo Spadafora, one of Noriega's most outspoken
critics, in September 1985.
   Quayle said he met Spencer for the first time last month when he
became George Bush's running mate and Spencer, a veteran of both
Reagan presidential campaigns, came to handle his campaign.
   ``I did not know about this'' at the time, Quayle said,
referring to Spencer's lobbying for Noriega.
   However, Quayle noted that Spencer's consulting contract had
expired several years ago and that Spencer had advised Panama's
civilian president at the time, Eric Arturo Delvalle, that Panama
should be run by a civilian rather than military government.
Noriega ousted Delvalle in February.
   ``They'd be in a much better situation had they accepted his
advice on that. That's about all I know,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle reaffirmed his position that ``Noriega has got to go ...
the sooner the better.'' When asked whether that statement also
applied to Spencer, Quayle replied, ``No.''
   Bush, meeting with reporters outside his Washington residence,
also defended Spencer. ``Panama's a friendly country,'' Bush said.
``And as he made clear, I think, Delvalle was the president under
which he was hired. So I have no concerns about that. And I think
he explained it pretty well.''
   Quayle was also asked to elaborate on his comment Friday that
the decision of Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis to
rehire former top aide John Sasso as his campaign vice chairman
meant that Dukakis' campaign was in serious trouble.
   Sasso resigned in September 1987 after admitting that he
circulated a videotape of Sen. Joseph Biden using a British
politician's rhetoric without attribution.
   ``I guess you would say that the liberal furlough policy of the
governor of Massachusetts is still in place,'' Quayle said, a jibe
at the state's weekend prison-release program. Dukakis signed a
bill cutting back the program after a murderer on a weekend
furlough raped a Maryland woman.
   At an arts and crafts fair in Newnan, Ga., a reporter asked
Quayle if he was concerned that Georgia voters might be swayed by
Sen. Sam Nunn, a Democrat and Dukakis supporter, when it came to
their presidential choice. Nunn is chairman of the Senate Armed
Services Committee, a committee on which Quayle serves.
   ``This is a pro-defense state. The pro-defense presidential
choice is is George Bush, not Michael Dukakis,'' Quayle said.
   During his visit to the fair, Quayle was given a rocking chair
and a sketch depicting a turkey-calling contest. On the sketch, in
a reference to the news media, was an inscription which read, ``No
matter how loud they gobble they are still turkeys.''
   Quayle and his wife Marilyn have said they feel reporters have
been overzealous in pursuing various controversies about the
senator's military service, academic record and personal life.
   After the Georgia appearances, Quayle traveled to Columbia,
S.C., where he attended the University of South Carolina football
season opener against the University of North Carolina.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
