<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BadmintonSlaying     09-03 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Badminton Slaying,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gandhi Foe Questioned In Slaying Of India's Badminton Champ</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal authorities arrested a political
foe of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi on Saturday and accused him of
conspiring to murder India's top badminton player after having an
affair with the sportsman's wife.
   Opposition leaders said the suspect, Sanjay Singh, was the
victim of a political vendetta. He also was defended by the wife of
the badminton star.
   Singh, 32, was arrested in Lucknow, the capital of Uttar Pradesh
state, in connection with the July 28 slaying of Syed Modi, India's
top-ranked badminton player, said an official of the Central Bureau
of Investigation.
   Authorities have evidence that Singh had an affair with Modi's
wife, Ameeta, and conspired with her to murder the sportsman, said
the official. The official, based in New Delhi, cannot be
identified under briefing rules.
   Under Indian law, formal charges must be brought within 90 days
and a prosector must explain the grounds Singh's arrest within 24
hours.
   Soon after the arrest, Mrs. Modi, 24, said the killer was still
free. ``I cannot believe Sanjay Singh could murder my husband,''
she told the United News of India news agency in Lucknow. ``He was
Modi's closest friend.''
   The arrest also drew criticism from Jan Morcha, or People's
Movement, an opposition group to which Singh belongs. ``I am not
surprised at the arrest,'' said Arun Nehru, a party leader and
Gandhi's cousin. ``It is the natural culmination of a motivated
investigation.''
   Jan Morcha broke away from Gandhi's governing Congress Party and
is highly critical of the prime minister. Singh is not a
politically powerful outside Uttar Pradesh but he commands
considerable influence in Amethi, the prime minister's
parliamentary constituency.
   Singh was a close ally of Gandhi and his campaign manager during
the last elections to Parliament in 1985. Singh is the scion of the
former royal family of Amethi, and although titles were abolished
in India in 1971, former maharajahs and princes still have a large
following.
   Singh fell out with Gandhi last year after differences with the
Uttar Pradesh chief minister. When Gandhi sided with the chief
minister, the highest elected official in the state, Singh quit the
Congress Party. He has vowed not to let Gandhi win any further
elections from Amethi.
   Modi, 28, was shot with a Colt .38-caliber revolver as he
stepped out of a Lucknow sports stadium, where had gone for his
customary evening round of practise. The Uttar Pradesh government
asked the Central Bureau of Investigation, patterned on the FBI, to
take over the case on Aug. 2.
   On Aug. 16, bureau detectives arrested four people, including an
associate of Singh, on murder charges. Ameeta Modi was later
arrested on charges of conspiring in the murder after unidentified
sources in the bureau told newspapers they had evidence that she
had an affair with Singh.
   Mrs. Modi was released on bail when she said she had no one to
care for her 6-month-old daughter. In India, people arrested on
murder charges usually are not released on bail.
   Singh was questioned several times by investigators in recent
weeks. On a visit to New Delhi last week, he told reporters: ``This
is the worst kind of political vendetta. The Prime Minister and his
coterie are using government agencies to intimidate the opposition.
Their plan is to discredit me in order to give Rajiv Gandhi a
victory in the next general elections.''
   His Lucknow residence was also searched by detectives of the
bureau, and the search drew sharp criticism after it was televised
on state-owned national television.
   ``They want to try Sanjay Singh through electronic media,'' said
Arif Mohammed Khan, also a Jan Morcha leader. ``They want to finish
him.''
</TEXT>
