<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp     09-03 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Wind Up Pre-Labor Day Campaigns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The presidential candidates wound up their pre-Labor Day
campaigns Saturday with Democrat Michael Dukakis paying a
sentimental visit to Ellis Island and Republican George Bush
pointedly praising his opponent's debating skills.
   ``He's probably a better debater,'' Bush said of the
Massachusetts governor, adding quickly: ``I'm lowering
expectations.''
   In an outdoor news conference followed by a picnic for reporters
at his vice presidential residence on the grounds of the U.S. Naval
Observatory in Washington, Bush refrained from the fiery attacks
that dominated his campaign speeches last week.
   However, Dukakis started his day by attacking Bush's
insensitivity to the plight of the unemployed.
   Bush on Friday called an increase in the jobless rate from 5.4
percent in July to 5.6 percent in August ``statistically almost
irrelevant.''
   Dukakis seized on that Saturday, telling supporters outside his
hotel in Sioux Falls, S.D., that the increase meant ``another
200,000 people without jobs.''
   He continued his criticism of Bush's remark later, adding it to
a speech at Ellis Island in New York.
   ``We must never forget _ although some already have _ that no
one in America is irrelevant,'' Dukakis said. ``In America everyone
matters; we stand by our neighbors.''
   Dukakis' trip to Ellis Island was a sentimental and symbolic
journey on which he was accompanied by his 85-year-old mother,
Euterpe. An immigrant from Greece, she landed there 76 years ago on
her arrival in the United States.
   ``America's story is the immigrants' story,'' Dukakis said.
``Newcomers arriving, some on slave ships to our lasting shame;
some on converted coal ships like my mother, immigrants from every
corner of Earth, drawn by the torch of freedom.''
   Dukakis also was accompanied by New York Gov. Mario Cuomo,
himself the son Italian immigrants, who hailed the Democratic
nominee for standing ``on the edge of realizing the immigrant
fantasy: He is about to become the president of the United States
of America.''
   Cuomo was among some dozen political leaders who were expected
to be named this week as co-chairmen of the Dukakis campaign.
Others included Sen. John Glenn of Ohio, Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia
and Gov. Madelyn Kunin of Vermont, according to a campaign source
who demanded anonymity.
   Politically, the trip to the island was a reminder of Dukakis'
ethnic roots as the Democrats try to win back the ethnic voters who
cast Republican ballots for Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984.
   Bush, meanwhile, said a two-day break in campaigning this
weekend is ``a good time to take stock of where things stand.''
   He said he was not concerned about questions arising over Stuart
Spencer, campaign manager for vice presidential running mate Dan
Quayle. Spencer's lobbying firm was paid more than $350,000 in l985
and 1986 to assist the Panamanian government headed by Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   Quayle, campaigning in Atlanta, also defended Spencer.
   ``I believe that his political experience and political guidance
has been and will be valuable to me,'' Quayle said.
   On the presidential debates, Bush said he had no intention of
changing his stand on the number of face-to-face encounters between
the candidates. Bush has agreed to two televised debates, while
Dukakis wants three.
   ``We've made a strong proposal that calls for two debates at
this level and one at the vice presidential level and we're going
to stay with it,'' Bush said. ``I think it's the right amount of
this kind of campaign activity.''
   ``He's favored in the debates, there's no doubt about it,'' Bush
said of Dukakis. ``My wife Barbara, when I practice debating, she
falls asleep. And I've got to do something different about that.''
   In debates, as elsewhere in politics, a candidate's performance
is measured by how well he was expected to do. Bush clearly was
trying to lower the expectations for his performance while raising
the stakes for Dukakis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
