<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     09-03 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Clash; Shiite Leader Blames US For Election Impasse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Palestinian factions with mortars
and rocket-propelled grenades clashed in a south Beirut refugee
camp Saturday, killing three people and wounding nine, police said.
   In another development, the most senior Shiite Moslem cleric in
Lebanon blamed the United States and Israel for Parliament's
failure to elect a new president and said it will ``explode in
their face.''
   Guerrillas of George Habash's Marxist Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine fought Syrian-backed fighters of Col. Saeed
Mousa's Fatah-Uprising for five hours.
   A police spokesman said the clash at the Bourj el-Barajneh
refugee camp stopped after neutral guerrilla groups called a
cease-fire.
   ``Police patrols couldn't enter the camp to launch an
investigation,'' said the spokesman, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   He said the casualties were evacuated to hospitals in west
Beirut.
   The Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine operates under
the umbrella of Yasser Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Mousa broke away from the PLO in 1983 and established
headquarters in Damascus, the Syrian capital.
   Guerrillas of Arafat's mainline Fatah group evacuated Bourj
el-Barajneh, their last foothold in Beirut, on July 8 after the
camp fell to Mousa's followers.
   The Shiite leader, Sheik Mohammed Mehdi Shamseddin, said said an
``American-Israeli plot'' was behind Parliament's failure on Aug.
18 to muster a quorum of 51 members to elect a new president.
   ``If the Americans want to continue with their dangerous game,
then a force stronger than what they have known will explode in
their face,'' he said.
   The only serious candidate was Syrian-backed warlord Suleiman
Franjieh, 78. According to Lebanon's Constitution, a new head of
state should be elected before Sept. 23, when the six-year term of
President Amin Gemayel expires.
   Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini, a Shiite, adjourned the
abortive election session without setting a date for a new meeting
to elect a president.
   Syrian-backed leftist and Moslem factions have accused the
United States and the right-wing Christian Lebanese Forces militia,
which is sympathatic to Israel, of blocking Franjieh's election.
   Franjieh's backers have also accused the Lebanese Forces of
forcefully preventing deputies from attending the parliamentary
session to block the election of Franjieh, a personal friend of
Syrian President Hafez Assad.
   The Christian militia has denied the charge and said the
boycotters opposed Franjieh's election. But a Lebanese Forces
spokesman, speaking privately, said Parliament will have ``no
quorum as long as Franjieh remains a candidate.''
   U.S. State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley has blamed
Parliament's failure to elect a new president on the lack of a
``consensus candidate.''
   Shamseddin, addressing a news conference at his residence in
Moslem west Beirut, said the United States ``wants to end Syria's
regional (Middle Eastern) role to give Israel a free hand in
Lebanon.''
   ``We are determined not to succumb to the American stand,'' said
Shamseddin, who heads the Supreme Shiite Islamic Council in Lebanon.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 40,000 troops
in eastern and northern provinces and in west and south Beirut.
</TEXT>
