<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Brites     09-03 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Tavilla stood at the base of Boston's
60-story John Hancock Tower, head back, mouth open, as grapes
rained down around him at 110 mph.
   Some hit the building. Quite a few splattered on the concrete.
But shortly after noon Saturday, on about his 70th try, the
gray-haired, 54-year-old Tavilla finally caught one in his mouth _
and about 150 spectators burst into applause.
   Chalk up another grape-catching record for Tavilla. At 788 feet,
it easily topped his previous best, recorded by the Guinness Book
of World Records as 660 feet from the top of the Sumitomo Insurance
Building in Tokyo, Japan, on March 1, 1986.
   Catching grapes is no picnic, insists Tavilla, a produce
merchant from Arlington.
   ``It's very, very dangerous if you don't know what you're
doing,'' he warned. ``You could put out an eye.''
   Then there's the neck strain.
   ``It absolutely kills me,'' he confessed.
   So why does he do it?
   ``I was always good at catching things in my mouth when I was a
kid,'' he said. ``It's fun. Plus they taste good.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Though he helped raise goats as a boy,
Mayor Bill Harris proved udderly helpless in the goat-milking
contest at the Nebraska State Fair.
   Harris pumped out barely more than a mouthful of the stuff
Friday and placed last in the competition.
   Eight men had two minutes to milk their Nebraska-bred goat. The
winner was Larry Hudkins of rural Malcolm, who squeezed out two
quarts.
   ``It was a tough race. But I had a good goat,'' Hudkins said.
   Harris blamed his last-place performance on his goat, as well.
   ``With a name like Sam, what can you expect?''
</TEXT>
