<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NorthernIreland     09-03 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Supporters, Victims Bury Their Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUNMOYLE, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed soldiers lined narrow
roads in this remote village Saturday as thousands of mourners
followed the funeral cortege of an IRA guerrilla, one of three men
killed in an ambush by British soldiers.
   A Protestant leader bitterly protested the presence at the
funeral of the dead man's brother, another IRA guerrilla who was
released from prison to attend the service.
   Across the province in Londonderry, family and friends gathered
to mourn a man and a woman who went to check on a neighbor but
instead stumbled into an explosive booby trap laid for British
soldiers.
   The Irish Republican Army apologized for the bombing deaths of
Sean Dalton, 55, and Sheila Lewis, 60, but the clergyman who gave
their eulogies had a bitter reply.
   ``We do not want to hear any more apologies from the IRA or from
anyone else,'' Edward Daly, the Catholic bishop of Londonderry,
told the mourners.
   ``We want an end to all this death and destruction, which is
destroying our city and destroying our people and destroying the
chances for the young people coming along for work, for
opportunity,'' Daly said.
   Dalton broke into the neighbor's apartment on Wednesday and
triggered a bomb rigged by the IRA, which had kidnapped the
occupant and planned to blow up any army squad that came to check
on the missing man. The IRA apologized, saying the operation went
``tragically wrong.''
   As the families of the dead mourned in the two towns, a British
military base in Crossmaglen near the South Armagh border came
under mortar attack. Police said two of the three shells that
exploded landed inside the heavily fortified base but that there
were no injuries and little damage.
   In Dunmoyle, police and soldiers stood guard as mourners
followed the cortege of 26-year-old Brian Mullin, one of three IRA
men shot to death Tuesday by the waiting army as the guerrillas
drove along a country road on what the IRA called ``active duty.''
   News reports said Mullin and brothers Gerard Harte, 29, and
Martin Harte, 21, were about to try to kill an off-duty member of
the Protestant Ulster Defense Regiment when soldiers lying in wait
riddled their stolen car with bullets.
   The Harte brothers were buried Friday.
   Among the mourners at Dunmoyle was Mullin's elder brother,
Patrick, released on a day's compassionate leave from Belfast's
Maze prison, where he is serving a life sentence for the 1977 IRA
murder of a school bus driver _ another mistaken killing for which
the IRA apologized.
   Ken Maginnis, a member of the Protestant Official Unionist
Party, expressed outrage over the release.
   ``It is an absolute scandal that this man who is one of a
committed IRA family, should be released, or paroled or whatever it
is called,'' Maginnis said.
   ``The concession for the funeral of a terrorist involved in the
murder of eight young soldiers exactly 14 days ago is a concession
to IRA terrorism quite beyond comprehension.''
   Maginnis is among those who believe Brian Mullin was involved in
the bus bombing that killed eight British soldiers Aug. 20 and
injured 27 others _ the worst incident so far of the IRA's
heated-up campaign to drive the British out of the predominantly
Protestant province and unite it with the Roman Catholic Irish
Republic.
   Patrick Mullin was delayed at a security checkpoint and the
cortege of about 2,000 mourners did not leave the family farm at
Sixmilecross, 50 miles west of Belfast, until about noon, an hour
later than scheduled.
   More than 200 police and soldiers accompanied the hearse
carrying Mullin's coffin, which was draped with the Irish tricolor
flag, along four miles of winding country roads from Sixmilecross
to Dunmoyle for the funeral and burial.
</TEXT>
