<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Suicides     09-03 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Suicides,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Set Up Suicide Hotline For Troubled Teen-Agers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moscow authorities opened a suicide prevention
center and set up a telephone hotline for troubled teen-agers after
a surge in suicides among young people, including a 7-year-old, the
government newspaper said Saturday.
   Izvestia drew a link between a rise in suicides and increased
alcohol and drug abuse.
   ``Among teen-agers, the abuse of alcohol and cigarettes, drug
and toxic substances ... is spreading,'' the newspaper said. It
said specialists regarded the growing abuse as proof of ``conscious
or unconscious striving toward physical and moral
self-destruction.''
   In one case, a 7-year-old killed himself, the newspaper said.
   The Moscow center, which opened Sept. 1, will be staffed by
medical personnel skilled at easing stress and depression, Izvestia
said. It said specialists believe the hotline, or ``telephone of
trust,'' is the most effective means of offering psychological
counseling.
   Moscow has more than 20 psychological aid centers where people
can seek help anonymously. It also has had a ``telephone of trust''
for 15 years.
   But now teen-agers will have a hotline of their own that they
can call if they want counseling.
   Izvestia did not give the number of the teen-agers' hotline or
say how capital residents could get it. It said the teen-age
suicide rate for Moscow was ``closed information.''
   In June, the weekly newspaper Arguments and Facts reported that
the national suicide rate for people of all ages was about 20 per
100,000 members of the population. That would be about 56,000
suicides a year.
   According to a 1985 U.N. report, the suicide rate in the United
States in 1982 was 12.2 per 100,000 residents.
   The more recent candor about the suicide problem in the Soviet
Union is a consequence of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
endorsement of ``glasnost,'' or greater openness, in the discussion
of selected social issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
