<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Shuttle-Indictment     09-03 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Indictment,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Parts Supplier Indicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California supplier of bolts that were
to be used on a piece of equipment aboard the space shuttle was
indicted on charges of mail fraud and making false statements to
NASA.
   Arthur O. Sammons, contacted by telephone at his home in Los
Angeles, said Saturday that he had not been informed of the
43-count indictment, returned by a grand jury Friday.
   ``I don't know anything about it. Let's just say no comment on
that one,'' he said. Sammons declined to discuss his business but
said he was the only person with his name in the Canoga Park
section of Los Angeles.
   The grand jury charged that Sammons, identified as a
manufacturer and distributor of aerospace fasteners, signed false
certifications saying that bolts supplied under a contract to
Teledyne Brown Engineering in Huntsville had been tested as
required by NASA standards.
   In fact the bolts, used on a piece of equipment known as Astro
I, were not properly examined, the charges state. Astro I was to be
installed in the space shuttle, said the indictment.
   Last fall, in a schedule of planned shuttle flights from 1988 to
1990, NASA said Astro I was one of the pieces of scientific
equipment that would be used on a flight during that period. The
schedule described it as an ultraviolet observatory.
   Engineers with the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
estimated the cost of identifying, removing and replacing the
suspect bolts on Astro 1 at $1 million.
   Sammons was indicted on 26 counts of making false statements to
NASA, said U.S. Attorney Frank Donaldson. He also was indicted on
17 counts of mail fraud stemming from bills he sent to Teledyne
Brown for the parts, the prosecutor said.
   If convicted of all charges, Sammons would face up to 215 years
in prison and a $7.83 million fine, said a spokesman for
Donaldson's office. Sammons' arraignment is scheduled for Sept. 15.
</TEXT>
