<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Afghan     09-03 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Afghan,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistan Rejects Afghan Proposal For New Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan on Saturday rejected an
Afghan proposal for another international conference to discuss the
U.N.-backed agreement calling for the withdrawal of Soviet troops
from Afghanistan.
   Afghanistan suggested another conference of representatives from
Pakistan, Afghanistan, the United States and the Soviet Union to
follow the pact signed April 14 in Geneva, with the United States
and Soviets serving as guarantors.
   A key provision of the Geneva pact was the withdrawal of about
115,000 Soviet military personnel from Aghanistan. The Soviets sent
troops into the neighboring country in December 1979 to help the
Marxist government battle anti-communist rebels.
   Western diplomats in Islamabad said it appeared the Afghan
government wants a followup conference because of increased rebel
attacks on the withdrawing Soviet troops and Afghan security
forces. The Kremlin has said half of the Soviets had been pulled
out by the stipulated date of May 15 and all will be out of
Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
   Pakistan's Foreign Affairs Ministry issued a statement Saturday
rejecting the Afghan proposal for a second conference. It said ``it
should be noted that the Geneva agreements contain provisions with
respect to implementation'' of the accords.
   The statement said the pact and an accompanying memorandum of
understanding provide procedures ``to consider alleged violations
and to work out prompt and mutually satisfactory solutions to
questions that may arise in the implementation of the instruments.''
   Abdul Wakil, the Afghan foreign minister, suggested a new
conference in a letter last week to U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cueller.
   Both Afghanistan and Pakistan accuse each other of violating the
April agreement.
   Afghanistan and the Soviet Union claim Pakistan and the United
States continue to provide support to the rebels in volation of the
accord. Pakistan and the United States accuse the Soviet and Afghan
forces of terrorist activities and bombings in Pakistan. Washington
on Friday protested the bombing of Kunduz in northern Afghanistan
by Soviet aircraft.
   A U.N. mission established under the Geneva agreement is
operating in Afghanistan and Pakistan and both countries have filed
complaints with the mission.
   The Pakistani Foreign Ministry statement said that is the proper
procedure for complaining about violations.
   It said Afghanistan's request for another conference on
implementation of the accords ``appears to be no more than a
propaganda measure designed to acquire international recognition
and legitimacy.''
   The statement said that on Sept. 1, soon after Afghanistan
proposed the conference, five Afghan aircraft violated Pakistani
airspace and bombed two villages, ``killing a number of civilians.''
</TEXT>
