under the seat of his locked car, which was parked next to his
business, Westerville Service Center.
   Some airplane navigational charts and equipment, a pilot's
license and receipts from his business also were taken, he said.
   Stone said police and neighborhood children told him someone had
told the children when to burglarize his car and what to look for.
He thinks the thieves initially took only his flying gear and the
receipts, then returned for the cash.
   About $20,000 has been recovered, including about $7,000
returned to Stone by a youngster who was not charged, police said.
