<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RareBat     09-03 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rare Bat,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biologists Thrilled To Find Pregnant Bat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORAL GABLES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Biologists were thrilled to find a
species of bat that some feared had slipped into extinction, then
they were ecstatic to learn the tiny Florida mastiff bat was
pregnant.
   ``This means there's not just one, but three _ mom, dad and
baby,'' wildlife biologist Frank Mazzotti said after an X-ray
examination disclosed the pregnancy.
   No Florida mastiff bat, found only in southeastern Florida, had
been identified since 1978.
   The 5{-inch flying mammal bat turned up early last week on the
balcony of a Coral Gables office and was handed over to specialists.
   Bat specialist Mark Robson of the state Game and Fresh Water
Fish Commission was thrilled to see the animal, but alarmed that it
appeared so sick.
   ``It didn't try to fly or bite. We speculated that it ran into
the building the night before and sort of got stunned, and when it
lay there all day it got worse,'' Robson said.
   Its blood sugar and body temperature were dangerously low and
the bat was pronounced in critical condition.
   Robson rushed the bat to the Pembroke Pine Animal Clinic, where
it was treated for dehydration.
   By Friday, it weighed a robust one and one-third ounces and
experts planned to let it fly away at dusk. That plan changed when
they discovered the advanced pregnancy.
   The rare bat was given a place in a maternity basket at the
clinic while wildlife experts search for more of her kind.
</TEXT>
