<HEAD>Man Accused Of Trying To Hire `Hit Man' To Cripple Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of giving an undercover cop
money and a gun to shoot and cripple a former girlfriend has been
charged with conspiracy to commit first-degree assault.
   John Joseph Kotowski of Roseville, reported to be in his late
20s, was arraigned Friday before Ramsey County District Judge
Margaret Marrinan. He was ordered held Friday on bail of $100,000.
   Kotowski was arrested Thursday in a St. Paul parking lot after
allegedly giving a .32-caliber handgun, 41 rounds of ammunition,
$670, photographs of the woman and addresses she frequented to a
man he thought was a professional ``hit man,'' according to a
complaint filed by authorities.
   The man, D.G. Owens, actually was an agent of the Minnesota
Bureau of Criminal Apprehension.
   The complaint says Kotowski told the agent he wanted the
29-year-old woman put in a wheelchair for life because she was
``vain'' and had stolen an ounce of cocaine from him.
   The agent was asked ``to severely injure the unidentified female
by shooting her in the back and hopefully paralyzing her for
life,'' the complaint says.
   Kotowski also allegedly told the agent that he would have done
the shooting himself if he could have found a gun with a silencer.
   Kotowski and Owens had a series of meetings and phone calls over
3{ months before the arrest, according to the complaint. Owens
warned Kotowski that it would be difficult merely to wound the
woman and that she might be killed.
   ``Kotowski indicated that he understood and told Owens to go for
broke,'' the complaint says.
