<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HonorFlunking     09-03 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honor Flunking,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>You're On The Honor Roll, Kid, But You Flunk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pupils given A's and B's for their
self-esteem and then told they had flunked third grade will be
allowed to attend fourth grade this fall after all, school
officials say.
   The fight started after a teacher at Alum Creek Elementary
School, who has since quit, flunked 13 of 18 third-graders at the
end of the school year. Some of the children had received A's and
B's and even had made the honor roll.
   Angry parents demanded to know how their children could
seemingly do so well and still flunk.
   Jo Ann Litton, a Kanawha County elementary schools director,
said the school had given the youngsters good grades and honors to
avoid giving them ``a poor self-concept.''
   The county agreed to put the children in the fourth grade if
they passed comprehensive tests. All eight of the students taking
the tests last week did well enough to be promoted, said Alum Creek
acting principal Eulah Mae Fleming.
   Litton said she decided that the rest of the students should be
promoted also, though only on a nine-week, probationary status.
   ``They were sent into the fourth grade with a very competent
teacher, and we think she'll do a lot for them,'' Ms. Fleming said.
</TEXT>
