<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Disasters     09-03 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Disasters,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Seeks International Aid for Disaster-Struck Provinces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China will accept foreign aid for three provinces
hit hard by natural disasters that have taken 500 lives and caused
nearly $2 billion in damages, the official Xinhua news agency said
Saturday.
   Severe weather in Zhejiang, Heilongjiang and Hubei provinces
also affected the lives of more than 25 million people, according
to a report from the Ministry of Civil Affairs, the agency said.
   In an indirect appeal for aid, Xinhua said, ``The Chinese
authorities have taken various measures to help the disaster areas.
... Help from foreign countries and international organizations
will be accepted.''
   It said the three provinces lack money and supplies including
edible oil, grain, cloth, cement, fertilizer, medicine and material
for rebuilding houses and factories.
   The report did not give any amount of money or supplies needed.
   Xinhua said the coastal Zhejiang province was struck by floods,
droughts and typhoons while grain output in Hubei province will be
reduced by 3 million tons because of a drought that has affected
much of central China.
   Floods in northeastern Heilongjiang province have inundated
nearly half of the crop land, the agency said.
   Xinhua reported earlier that flooding in coastal and
northeastern provinces had claimed a total of 1,406 lives by
mid-August.
