<DOCNO> AP880903-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 1906EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeenCharged     09-03 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teen Charged,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Charged With Shooting Stranger With High-powered Rifle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old boy who friends called
``Little Rambo'' told police he ``just wanted to get away from
everything and kill somebody'' when he drove to a neighboring state
and shot to death a woman he didn't know, authorities said.
   Chris Swatzell, described by friends as a well-behaved boy with
an interest in military lore, was in custody Saturday in a
Nashville, Tenn., mental health center for tests to see if he is
competent to stand trial.
   He faces capital murder charges in the killing of Carolyn
Kilpatrick, 41, who was found dead Monday in a shop behind her home
near Linden, Tenn.
   Police said the boy, who had never been in trouble with the law,
turned himself in and confessed to killing Mrs. Kilpatrick, 41. She
was shot four times with a high-powered rifle.
   ``To look at him, you would just picture him as an all-around,
all-American boy,'' said Betty Kelso, manager of a Hardee's
restaurant where Swatzell worked as a cook.
   ``He wasn't a 16-year-old who was out to conquer the world.
Something must have happened.''
   Perry County, Tenn., Sheriff Thomas Ward said the killing
occurred about 2 p.m. Monday, about five hours after Swatzell left
unexcused from Caldwell County High School in Princeton.
   Ward said the teen-ager went home, got two of his stepfather's
high-powered, military-type rifles and drove southward into
Tennessee.
   Recounting Swatzell's confession, Ward said the boy passed Mrs.
Kilpatrick's home, six miles west of Linden, Tenn., which is about
120 miles from Princeton.
   Mrs. Kilpatrick was working in a furniture refinishing shop
behind her house, Ward said. Swatzell drove into the driveway,
walked to the doorway of the shop and shot her four times with a
semi-automatic AR-15 similar to a deer rifle.
   ``He said he just wanted to get away from everything and kill
somebody,'' Ward said. ``He said he had been wanting to do it for
about three months.''
   Swatzell hitched a ride to Parsons, Tenn., where he turned
himself in, about the time Mrs. Kilpatrick's husband found his
wife's body.
   Police found the AR-15 rifle and a second, similar rifle in the
boy's abandoned car, and found a bayonet and gun-cleaning kit in
his military-style knapsack.
   Ward said Swatzell's stepfather, David Braden, a Kentucky prison
officer, collected military-type guns, and Swatzell often went to a
firing range near Princeton.
   The sheriff said the boy's friends nicknamed him ``Little
Rambo'' and ``G.I. Joe'' because of his interest in military gear,
but the boy's behavior did not suggest he was a fanatic about such
things.
   His mother ``told us he liked Rambo, but he wasn't obsessed with
that sort of thing,'' Ward said. ``He seems to be a very average
boy, never in any trouble. It's strange.''
   Brenda Stephens, Caldwell County High School's guidance
counselor, said Swatzell used to often wear fatigues _ but so did
many other students his age.
   ``Lately, he wasn't projecting that image,'' she said. ``He wore
blue jeans and T-shirts.''
   Ms. Stephens said she didn't meet often with Swatzell because
his grades were average to good and he had no disciplinary problems.
   ``He wasn't a joiner,'' she said. ``He had a very close circle
of friends and just minded his own business.''
</TEXT>
