<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusCrash     09-03 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tour Bus Accident Kills One Passenger, 29 Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRBANKS, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers on a tour bus were showered
with broken glass when the bus slipped off a muddy highway and
plunged 200 feet down an embankment in a remote area, a passenger
said.
   One passenger was killed and 29 remained hospitalized Saturday
in Fairbanks, about 110 miles west of the crash site near the
Canadian border.
   The bus traveling down a muddy stretch of the Taylor Highway, 23
miles south of Eagle, went off the road Friday afternoon after
meeting a fuel truck on the windy, unpaved roadway, Alaska State
Troopers said.
   Gray Line of Alaska said Saturday that 43 people were aboard the
bus. The company initially said the coach was carrying 41
passengers and a driver.
   ``It was a narrow stretch of road and we met a tanker truck,''
said Weldon Smith, a passenger from Waco, Texas.
   Passengers were lying or sitting in broken glass when the bus
came to a stop, said Frank Hochstein, 69, of New London, Conn. He
estimated rescuers reached the remote site about one hour after the
crash.
   Killed in the accident was Walter Meyerhoff, 57, of Vancouver,
British Columbia. Meyerhoff was traveling with his wife, Penny, who
was hospitalized in stable condition.
   Elizabeth Lambert of Ozark, Ala., said she saw the fuel truck
coming, felt a crunch as the bus left the road and ``the next thing
I knew I was thrown out of the bus, I guess through the front
window.'' She suffered facial cuts.
   Of the 29 people admitted to Fairbanks Memorial Hospital, one
was in critical condition and nine were in serious condition,
nursing supervisor Susan McLane said Saturday.
   The driver of the bus, David Kasser, 24, of Anchorage, suffered
superficial injuries and remained in Eagle, 23 miles from the crash
site, to meet with investigators, said Dave Bean, a spokesman for
Gray Line.
   The passengers were on the ninth day of a 15-day ``Klondike
Explorer'' tour, which included travel by boat, train and plane,
Bean said.
</TEXT>
