<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ToxicCargo     09-03 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toxic Cargo,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Ship Can Unload Toxic Cargo In Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wayward freighter carrying toxic wastes can
unload its unwanted cargo in Britain if it is properly contained
and documented, environmental officials said Saturday.
   ``If what was on the Karin B, or any other waste, is properly
identified, safely packaged, got the approval of waste disposal
authorities, is properly documented and complies with our laws,
there will be no problem,'' said an Environmental Department
spokesman in London, speaking anonymously in keeping with British
custom.
   In France, meanwhile, authorities said five sailors on the Karin
B have become ill but do not need immediate hospital treatment.
   The ship, with its leaking cargo, was turned away from Britain
last week and now is anchored in international waters off France's
Normandy coast.
   The Italian government announced Friday the ship would be
allowed to unload its cargo in Italy, probably at an unspecified
military port.
   France, Britain, Spain, West Germany, Belgium and the
Netherlands all refused entry to the Karin B, carrying 2,100 tons
of toxic wastes originally shipped from Italy and dumped illegally
in Nigeria.
   A statement issued Friday night by the maritime prefecture in
Cherbourg said a French navy doctor was taken by helicopter to
examine the crew members aboard the ship.
   The maritime prefecture statement said the five sailors
complained of pain in the chest and abdomen, while the rest of the
10-man crew, including the captain, reported no health problems.
   It said there would be further examinations of the ailing crew
members, but did not make clear whether they would sail with the
freighter to Italy.
   Italian officials have said they do not know the precise content
of the cargo, which may have originated from as many as 10 European
countries. The load was dumped secretly in Nigeria, whose
government insisted Italy remove them, and seized an Italian ship,
the Piave, last July to enforce its demands.
</TEXT>
