<2ND_LINE>AM-Singapore, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0634,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singapore's Governing Party Wins 80 of 81 Parliamentary Seats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to restore dropped word, percent, in
3rd graf; picks up 4th pvs: Lee, 64...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew led his People's
Action Party to its eighth straight election victory since 1959,
winning 80 seats in the recently enlarged 81-member Parliament.
   There had been no doubt that the People's Action Party would
win. When counting was completed Sunday, the party had won 69 of
the 70 seats contested in Saturday's balloting and 11 seats in
which its candidates were unopposed.
   Lee's party won 64.6 percent of final vote tally, compared with
64.8 percent in the previous election in 1984.
   Lee, 64, has been prime minister since 1959 when Singaore, a
former British colony, became self-governing. He is expected to
step down within the coming months and be succeeded by First Deputy
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong.
   ``I take great satisfaction from the results .... The transition
is complete. The future is up to my younger colleagues,'' Lee told
a news conference.
   Lee was re-elected easily in his constituency, defeating lawyer
M.G. Guru who ran as an independent 14,043 votes to 3,167.
   The last Parliament had 79 seats. PAP held 76, two were vacant
and Chiam See Tong, leader of the Singapore Democratic Party had
the other.
   Candidates from seven opposition parties and four independents
failed to win any seats.
   Seven constituencies were abolished recently and nine new ones
created because of population shifts.
   Chiam, who won the only seat Saturday not claimed by the
governing party, immediately challenged Lee to hold a referendum on
Lee's proposal to replace the country's largely ceremonial
presidency.
   The president now is selected by the prime minister and his
Cabinet. Under the Lee's pln, the president would be elected and
would have veto power over spending from the nation's financial
reserves and appointments to senior civil service and judicial
positions.
   The president would have access to all government departments
but would not have full executive power.
   Lee said a president with veto powers could guard the nation's
financial reserves if future governments tried to use the money
unwisely.
   It has been suggested Lee might run for the office in a
presidential election and he was asked about that at his news
conference.
   ``The proposal has not been tailored for me,'' he said. ``I'll
campaign in support of it but I don't want the job.''
   Another issue stressed by the PAP is the planned creation of
town councils in each parliamentary constituency to manage public
housing. About 86 percent of Singapore's 2.6 million people live in
government-built apartments that are now administered by civil
servants.
   PAP candidates told voters that inept legislators controlling
the civil service could neglect rubbish collection, elevator
repairs and other routine but chores.
   Chaim said the town-council concept was ``part of the PAP's
overall plan to reduce the role of Parliament, to pave the way for
an executive president.''
   The Internal Security Act, which allows the government to detain
suspects indefinately without charges, had not been a major issue.
   Critics claim the measure was abused by the government to deal
with people opposed Lee's policies.
   The law was used to jail 22 alleged Marxists last year and hold
opposition lawyer Francis Seow for 72 days this year. Seow was
accused of dealing with U.S. diplomats to recruit lawyers to oppose
PAP parliamentary candidates.
   Voting was compulsory for those 21 or older and more than 90
percent of the 1.45 million eligible cast ballots in the contested
distsricts.
</TEXT>
