<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Clergy     09-03 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Clergy,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African Official Warns of Crackdown on Clergy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minister of Law and Order
Adriaan Vlok warned that the government may soon begin a crackdown
on outspoken anti-apartheid clergymen.
   ``We must clip their wings, as we clipped those of the 19
revolutionary and activist organizations,'' Adriaan Vlok said,
referring to the government's February decision banning most
leading anti-apartheid groups.
   Vlok acknowledged that restrictions against church leaders would
bring a ``deafening condemnation,'' but he added, ``This is all
part of the propaganda plan against South Africa.
   ``The time has come for us to tear off the masks so that people
can see who are their friends and who are their enemies,'' he said
in his statement to Parliament on Friday.
   Vlok cited no religious leaders by name. Previously, he has been
harshly critical of anti-apartheid churchmen such as Archbishop
Desmond Tutu, winner of the 1984 Nobel Peace Prize; and Rev. Allan
Boesak, president of the World Alliance of Reformed Churches.
   Vlok also said authorities have arrested 18,911 people without
charge for more than 30 days during a 26-month-old state of
emergency. He said the figure includes 802 people detained since
June 10.
   Anti-apartheid groups say about 30,000 have been held for some
length of time.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
