<1ST_LINE>u a AM-OilSpill     09-03 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Spill,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tanker Hits Bottom, Leaks Tarlike Oil Into Mississippi River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tanker scraped the bottom of the
Mississippi River on Saturday, rupturing the hull and spilling
about 1 million gallons of thick, heavy oil into the channel, Coast
Guard officials said.
   Coast Guard Lt. Pat Galvin said the tanker, Esso Puerto Rico,
dragged the bottom of the river at about 5 a.m. The accident left a
10-by-4 hole in the ship's hull, damaging one tank aboard, he said.
   Galvin said the vessel was carrying a cargo of carbon black
feedstock oil, which is also known as aromatic tar. The leakage
wasn't discovered until the ship began to list about 3{ hours later
becaus the oil doesn't float, he said.
   The vessel, which is owned by Exxon Shipping Co., was bound from
the Exxon dock at Baton Rouge, La., to Rotterdam, The Netherlands.
   Exxon spokesman Les Rogers said the oil-product solidified when
it leaked into the river.
   ``We understand that there's no health threat. There's nothing
floating in the water,'' he said. ``We will be responsible for
whatever cleanup measures are taken. We always assume the
responsiblity when it's our vessel and our product.''
   A Coast Guard pollution-response team said a preliminary survey
indicated a loss of more than 23,000 barrels, or more than 1
million gallons, Galvin said.
   Rogers said the ship was fully loaded with about 185,000 barrels
when the accident occurred. ``Everything drained out of that one
compartment,'' Rogers said. ``There's nothing leaking now.''
   The ship was docked Saturday at Belle Chasse, La., which is
located about 20 miles down river from New Orleans.
</TEXT>
