<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Vladivostok     09-03 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Vladivostok,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Port of Vladivostok to Become Open City, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will soon allow foreigners into the
Pacific coast city of Vladivostok, which serves as home port of the
Soviet navy and has been closed to non-Soviets for decades,
Izvestia said Saturday.
   ``This is no accident,'' the government daily newspaper said in
announcing the change. ``First of all, it is a result of the new
political initiatives of our country.''
   Vladivostok has in recent years become a scene and a symbol of
new Soviet efforts for better relations with the country's eastern
neighbors. In 1986, Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev gave a major
speech there, calling for increased cooperation with Asian and
Pacific nations.
   Izvestia did not say when Vladivostok would become an open city.
But later this month, an international symposium on problems of the
Asia-Pacific region is to be held in the city.
   According to Vladivostok's first deputy mayor, K. Dulov,
Gorbachev told former Japanese prime minister Yasuhiro Nakasone
during their Moscow meeting in July that the Soviets were thinking
of allowing foreigners into the city of 565,000 people.
   Dulov, in an interview with Izvestia, said the international
Asia-Pacific symposium was proof of the ``serious intention to open
the city to all.''
   ``Of course, today many limitations still exist, as in any
border city,'' Dulov said. ``Questions are being formulated about
how to remove them. This will take time....''
   Izvestia quoted Dulov as saying it already did not merit the
label ``closed,'' since 300 foreign delegations visited last year,
as compared to only 14 in 1985.
   Izvestia said there were also plans to create joint ventures
with foreign firms and a ``free economic zone'' in the Vladivostok
area, which would presumably be impossible if the city retains its
closed status.
   According to a Soviet Foreign Ministry note delivered to Moscow
embassies in January 1978, the entire Pacific Maritime Region where
Vladivostok is located is off-limits to foreigners, save for the
cities of Khabarovsk and Nakhodka and the section of the
Transsiberian railway linking them.
   Elsewhere in the Soviet Union, vast tracts are closed to
foreigners, including most of the territory of the Baltic republics
of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania, and frontier areas adjacent to
China, Afghanistan, Iran, Turkey, Finland and Norway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
