<DOCNO> AP880903-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 2055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Australia-Referendum     09-03 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Australia-Referendum,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voters Defeat Constitutional Changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters on Saturday rejected proposed
changes in the constitution that opposition leaders said would have
benefited the present Labor Party government.
   One amendment would have have extended legislative terms for the
House of Representatives from three to four years, which would have
extended the current government's term by one year.
   With one-third of the ballots counted, Attorney General Lionel
Bowen conceded the four questions had been defeated. ``The saddest
thing is that it is likely to mean the end of any further move for
constitutional reform for at least a decade,'' he said.
   Bowen did not give any figures.
   There were 10.3 million eligible voters, but the final results
and turnout will not be known until Sunday because of the time
difference between the east and west coasts.
   Voters cast either ``Yes'' or ``No'' votes on each proposal.
   The opposition Liberal Party had campaigned against the
referendum, saying the changes would give more power to the federal
government of Prime Minister Bob Hawke.
   ``The Australian people have protected their constitution from
Labor's tampering,'' said Liberal leader John Howard. ``The whole
referendum campaign by the government has been a disgraceful waste
of the taxpayers money.''
   Voters cast ballots on the following proposals:
   _Setting four-year terms for members of both the House of
Representatives and Senate with elections to be held simultaneously
for the two chambers. At present elections for the house are held
every three years. Senators are elected for six-year terms with
half of the members elected every three years. _Change election
rules to provide each vote with the same value. Under the present
alignment of electoral districts, especially in the states of
Queensland and Western Australia, the vote in sparsely populated
rural districts has the same weight as the vote in populous urban
districts.
   _Constitutional recognition of local governments.
   _Constitutional guarantees to trial by jury, freedom of religion
and fair compensation for land owners whose property is acquired by
any government.
   Australia's constitution was adopted in 1901 when the country, a
former British colony, became an independent federation.
   There were no local governments at that time and the proposal
would have granted local governments constitutional recognition.
   Hawke had argued strongly for the changes in legislative terms,
saying four instead of three years was essential for any
administration to carry out its policies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
