<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Massacre     09-03 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Massacre,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Guerrillas Kill 18 Peasants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas killed 18 peasants in a
revenge raid against a farming hamlet that had organized security
patrols to protect against insurgents, police reported Saturday.
   They said about 60 guerrillas of the Shining Path movement
entered the hamlet of Chullos, rounded up the inhabitants and
killed 18 after accusing them of partipating in anti-insurgency
patrols.
   The guerrillas then ransacked and burned many homes in the
hamlet that has a population of about 200, according to police.
   They said the attack occurred Monday but was not reported for
days because Chullo is isolated in the Andean mountains. The hamlet
is 50 miles from the provincial capital of Ayacucho, which is 225
miles southeast of Lima.
   The military and police have organized citizens' patrols in
villages in the central Andes as protection against the guerrillas.
   In an attack Thursday against a civilian patrol near Parihuanca,
135 miles east of Lima, Maoist guerrillas killed a local politician
and a farm administrator, police said.
   They identified the slain patrol leader as Parihaunca Councilman
Humberto Calderon but did not give the identity of the farm
administrator.
   The Shining Path rebels began their campaign eight years ago
from strongholds in Ayachuco province.
   Since then more than 15,000 people have been killed in violence
related to the insurgency including hundreds of members of village
patrols, according to government reports.
</TEXT>
