<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--DeadWhale     09-03 0135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Dead Whale,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Huge Whale Washes Up on Beach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dead whale 76 feet long, tentatively
identified as a blue whale _ the world's largest animal species _
washed up on a beach near the southwest edge of San Francisco,
possibly early Saturday.
   ``It appears to be an adult blue whale,'' said Dr. Ray Dieter, a
veterinarian and chairman of the Coast Wildlife Society. He
estimated the whale's weight at over 150,000 pounds.
   Dieter said the creature was decomposing, and probably died last
week of undetermined causes. An attempt would be made to cart the
entire skeleton to a museum, possibly the California Academy of
Sciences in Golden Gate Park, he said.
   The Wildlife Society is conducting a marine mammal death and
population survey for the National Marine Fisheries Service.
</TEXT>
