<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Drugs     09-03 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Drugs,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Nine, Including Two Americans, In Drug Ring Bust</HEAD>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto MO-1</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal police said Saturday they have broken
up an international drug ring that had planned to fly more than
1,500 pounds of cocaine to California this weekend.
   They displayed the drugs and presented nine suspects, including
two Californians, at a news conference.
   Police said the seizure of 1,583 pounds of cocaine was one of
the largest hauls of cocaine in Mexico in recent years, although in
raids in December about 4,410 pounds were confiscated.
   A plane from the United States was scheduled to pick up the
cocaine from a warehouse at an airstrip in central Michoacan state
and fly it to California during the weekend, according to police.
   They said the Californians were arrested last week in
Guadalajara and identified them as Mike Baldrike of Santa Cruz and
Patrick Henry of Olympic Valley.
   Police said four Mexicans, a Colombian and a Nicaraguan also
were arrested during the investigation.
   They said the cocaine was from Medellin, Colombia, headquarters
of the Medellin cartel that is one of the largest cocaine
trafficking operations in the world.
</TEXT>
