<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BughouseDebates 1stLd-Writethru a0642 09-03 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bughouse Debates, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0642,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Revived Bughouse Square Debates Celebrate Free Speech Tradition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to update with crowd estimated, quotes
from speakers and new information on origin of Bughouse name. Picks
up 9th graf pvs, `Despres said...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long before Oprah, Phil and Geraldo, there was
Bughouse Square, an open-air talk show where bohemian
intellectuals, freethinkers and religious fundamentalists spoke
from soapboxes in a city park.
   That free speech tradition came to life again Saturday as about
300 people turned out for a revival of the Bughouse Square debates,
which faded from the scene in the 1950s with the coming of the
television age.
   ``Bughouse Square was and is a symbol of free speech ... and
it's a matter of honoring and reviving that tradition,'' said Leon
Despres, 80, the former city council parliamentarian, who was named
the informal master of ceremonies of this year's debates.
   ``It's a chance to get away from the whole TV-radio portrayal of
events,'' said Jennifer Jeffris, a spokeswoman for the Newberry
Library, sponsor of Saturday's debates.
   Organizers said they couldn't find any wooden soapboxes, but
they did scrounge up some library footstools and made a speaker's
platform out of a plastic milk crate and a wooden board.
   Julius Lucius Echeles, a prominent Chicago attorney, argued for
decriminalizing drugs, as some in the crowd shouted, ``We want to
keep drugs out of the country'' or ``What's the going price for
coke?''
   Other speakers held forth on such topics as the 1968 Chicago
Democratic convention riots, nationalized health care and the new
generation.
   Alderman Luis Gutierrez, who staged a surrogate Bush vs. Dukakis
presidential debate with Thomas F. Roeser, the founder of the
conservative Republican Assembly of Illinois, said he expected more
heckling.
   ``It's a lot calmer than a (Chicago) City Council meeting,''
said Gutierrez.
   The debates were revived as a once-a-year event in 1986 by the
Chicago Bar Association and the Newberry Library, which sits
opposite Bughouse Square, officially known as Washington Square
Park.
   Bughouse Square still attracts the occasional religious soapbox
preacher, but the library would like it once again to be a place
for debates on a regular basis, said Ms. Jeffris.
   One version of how the square got its name is that many park
frequenters were residents of nearby ``bughouses,'' a slang term
for flophouses, said Terry Sullivan, a Newberry Library spokeswoman.
   Despres said he wanted to revive another Bughouse tradition _
heckling.
   ``Nowadays, people are so respectful ...,'' said Despres, an
independent alderman from 1955-75 in a council dominated by Mayor
Richard J. Daley's Democratic machine. ``But you really have to
remember that from time to time a speaker should be challenged if
he makes an outrageous statement.''
   The Bughouse Square tradition, modeled after Speaker's Corner in
London's Hyde Park, got its start in the 1920s, although the park
itself is nearly 150 years old.
   Arthur Weinberg, a 72-year-old author and social historian, said
he often spoke there on labor struggles in the 1930s.
   At the time, Weinberg recalled, the speakers would be out seven
days a week during the summer. Chicagoans would to there on dates,
and tourists came as well.
   ``You got the same thing in Bughouse Square as on shows like
(Phil) Donahue,'' said Weinberg.
   ``But the freedom that happened there was really remarkable. I
can't think of one incident when the police interfered.''
   Weinberg said Bughouse Square was like ``an open-air adult
education school.'' Many of the speakers would research their
topics in the Newberry Library by day, before taking the soapbox at
night.
   But Bughouse Square died with the anti-radical mood of the
McCarthy era and the advent of television in the 1950s, he said.
   ``What Bughouse Square offered _ that radio and TV can't _ is
the touch and closeness of the speaker. You can listen to Dan
Rather, but you can't get close to him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
