<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WarehouseFire 1stLd-Writethru a0625 09-03 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Warehouse Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0625,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toxic Chemicals Burn As Firefighters Struggle To Douse Flames</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with fire under control, two
firefighters treated for heat exhaustion, cause under
investigation. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `We had...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dangerous fumes from burning toxic chemicals kept
firefighters at bay Saturday as they struggled to douse a
four-alarm warehouse blaze that took 14 hours to bring under
control, officials said.
   ``There were some chemicals in there, one of them was toluene.
It is a flammable. What makes it bad as a health hazard is the
fumes and exposure to it,'' said Metro-Dade Fire Department
spokesman John Carroll.
   No injuries were reported.
   The fire began about 4 a.m. at the warehouse in an industrial
area near Miami International Airport, and was brought under
control at 6 p.m. Two of the 100 firefighters on the scene were
treated for heat exhaustion.
   ``We really don't have a potential (toxic) cloud problem now,''
Carroll said, adding that environmental officials were at the scene.
   The cause of the fire was under investigation. No damage
estimate was immediately available, but Carroll said walls blew out
and items inside the warehouse were heavily damaged.
   The warehouse was used to store items awaiting U.S. Customs
clearance.
   While the fire spewed little smoke, its toxic fumes kept
firefighters away, said Carroll. Toluene is a poisonous, colorless
liquid used in making dyes, explosives or solvents.
   ``We had to cut holes in the roof for ventilation, and part of
the roof is sagging badly,'' he said.
   Officials at first thought the tons of merchandise in the
warehouse included 150 55-gallon drums of toluene but Carroll said
there may have been more.
   ``Literally a myriad of things are in there, like stereos and
some containers that are sealed, we don't know what's in there,''
he said.
   The department planned to bring in heavy equipment to dig
through the material to get to the fire, Carroll said.
   Several blocks around the warehouse were closed to traffic.
   ``But it's a non-residential area and no one was working that
time,'' he said. Officials weren't sure who owned the warehouse.
</TEXT>
