<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HurricaneUleki 3rdLd-Writethru a0656 09-03 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane Uleki, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0656,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Powerful Hurricane Plays Waiting Game With Hawaii</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: subs 3rd graf to UPDATE with later report of storm's center
location unchanged, new wind speeds</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Uleki resumed its march toward the
Hawaiian islands Saturday, slightly weakened but still posing a
considerable threat, forecasters reported.
   ``We hope it will weaken, so when it gets close, it will have
lost much of its punch,'' said meteorologist Clarence Lee of the
National Weather Service.
   At 2 p.m. (8 p.m. EDT) the storm was centered 325 miles south
southwest of Honolulu, or 345 miles south of Lihue, Kauai, with
maximum sustained winds of 100 mph and gusts to 120 mph, the
weather service said.
   Uleki was moving to the north at 2 to 3 mph, but that was
expected to pick up slightly to about 5 mph, Lee said.
   The storm had wind gusts up to 150 mph when it stalled about 360
miles south southeast of Honolulu on Friday night after making a
surprise turn towards the islands earlier in the day.
   ``Yesterday, the storm had a small, tight center. Today, it's a
large sprawling center. That's ususally an indication it is
weakening,'' Lee said.
   Even if Hawaii is spared the storm's worst winds, Uleki probably
will bring strong winds and rain to the islands sometime Sunday,
Lee said.
   ``Uleki is still a dangerous hurricane. Everyone should be
prepared,'' he said.
   A tropical storm watch was posted for the islands of Oahu, Kauai
and Niihau, meaning wind speeds of 39 mph to 73 mph were possible
through Sunday morning. A high surf advisory was posted for the
southern coasts of all islands.
   It was the second storm in a month to threaten the islands.
Hurricane Fabio was on a course toward the islands in early August
but then veered off and weakened, producing only some heavy rain on
parts of Kauai.
</TEXT>
