<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ForestFireRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0655 09-03 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fire Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0655,0846</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Battle Blazes In Record Heat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 15 grafs to UPDATE with residents of Montana towns
told to prepare to evacuate. Picks up 12th graf pvs `In Utah....'
SUBS 17th graf pvs, `Several heat...' with Saturday record
temperatures; SUBS last graf with Washington town preparing
evacuation contingency plan.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Smoke from Idaho's fires caused dangerous pollution Saturday,
fires near Yellowstone National Park threatened to merge and burn
into two Montana towns, and firefighters throughout the West
battled blazes in record or near-record heat.
   About 25,500 firefighters and support personnel are battling the
fires in the West, which have burned nearly 3.6 million acres this
summer, said Mike Ferris, spokesman at the federal Boise
Interagency Fire Center in Idaho.
   Fires also raged in Utah, Oregon, Washington and Wyoming.
   Idaho's Air Quality Bureau on Saturday placed the entire
southern part of the state under an air stagnation advisory,
because of limited visibility and air pollution caused by a pall of
smoke from the forest fires.
   ``The fires are funneling smoke along the entire Snake River
Valley,'' said bureau spokesman Orville Green. The advisory banned
outdoor burning and cautioned people with heart or respiratory
ailments to remain inside or curtail activity.
   Authorities knocked on doors of more than 150 recreation cabins
threatened by a forest fire in the Island Park area of northeastern
Idaho Saturday afternoon, warning residents to start packing for a
possible evacuation.
   In Montana, forest officials told residents of Cooke City and
Silver Gate near the Yellowstone Park boundary to prepare to leave
their homes as two fires burning in rugged, timber-covered terrain
approached.
   ``Things didn't go very well on the line today,'' fire
information officer Nick Tafoya said Saturday evening.
   The 57,000-acre Storm Creek fire was burning in
``firestorm-type'' conditions Saturday less than three miles from
Silver Gate and Cooke City, officials said.
   Forest Service spokesman Pat Kaunert said the several hundred
residents of these two gateway communities might have to evacuate
by early Sunday, leaving firefighters behind to fortify the area.
   On the nearby Hellroaring Creek fire, shifting winds Saturday
prompted postponement of plans to start backfires, spokesman Bill
Timko said. The 200-acre fire is expected to merge with the Storm
Creek blaze sometime this holiday weekend.
   That blaze forced officials Saturday to close the road from the
park's northeastern entrance.
   Winds largely pushed fires to the southwest Saturday, away from
West Yellowstone, Wyo., where volunteers put down 2 miles of
irrigation pipe to moisten the ground between the flames and the
tourist town.
   However, forecasts called for the winds to come from the
southwest again by Monday, which could blow the fire back toward
West Yellowstone.
   Park spokeswoman Amy Vanderbilt said firefighters placed an
emphasis on extinguishing a spot fire near West Yellowstone
Airport, as winds did not push the main body of the fire any closer
to the community than 1 mile.
   In Utah, four air tankers and a helicopter dropped chemical
retardant on a 1,500-acre brush fire Saturday as flames moved to
within 1,000 yards of more than 50 homes in Killyon Canyon east of
Salt Lake City.
   The homes were among more than 70 evacuated in the area late
Friday as high winds pushed flames through heavy scrub oak, said
Kathy Jo Pollock, spokeswoman for the Interagency Fire Center.
   ``Our top priority is to keep the fire away from those homes and
that's exactly what we're doing,'' said Pollock.
   Oregon officials hoped a forecast of lightning wouldn't come
true. They said the state's parched forests and rangelands would
erupt with new wildfires if lightning strikes.
   ``You could bet your house on it, really,'' said Don Ferguson, a
spokesman for the multiagency fire command center in Portland.
``There's probably a 90 percent ignition potential, meaning that
out of every 10 fire sources, nine of them will ignite a fire.''
   The National Weather Service said temperatures in the Northwest
were 20 degrees higher than normal on Saturday. Record high
temperatures were set in Kalispell, Mont., 97; Medford, Ore., 107;
Reddig, Calif., 116; Reno, Nev., 100; San Diego, Calif., 92; and
Yakima, Wash., 100.
   Fires burned Saturday on about 15,000 acres in seven parts of
Washington, said Ron DeHart of the U.S. Forest Service. Most were
caused by lightning in the northeastern part of the state.
   Despite progress in battling the blazes, officials feared the
effect of the heat.
   ``All these fires are real worries because any one of them can
blow up,'' DeHart said. ``Firefighters really have their work cut
out for them.''
   A 7,500-acre fire burning in Washington's Colville National
Forest jumped a highway at Sherman Pass, threatened a power line
and moved to within 10 miles of Republic, a town of about 1,000
people. Residents of a handful of rural homes northeast of town
were asked to leave, and officials drew up contingency plans to
evacuate the entire town, Ferry County Sheriff Richard Baldwin said.
</TEXT>
