<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 0113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Jorgensen     09-03 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Jorgensen,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transsexual Christine Jorgensen Battling Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN CLEMENTE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christine Jorgensen, the ex-G.I.
whose sex change operation nearly four decades ago led to a career
as a nightclub entertainer and writer, is battling spreading cancer.
   On Friday, she started a new round of chemotherapy treatments at
Mission Hospital Regional Medical Center in Mission Viejo in an
effort to stave off the cancer that has spread from her bladder to
her lungs.
   Fighting the disease is ``all-consuming and incredibly
inconvenient,'' she told The Orange County Register.
   Ms. Jorgensen, 62, learned she had cancer last year.
   The day Ms. Jorgensen learned she had the same disease that
killed her mother in 1967, Ms. Jorgensen went home and took a long
look at herself in her bathroom mirror.
   ``I said to myself, `Look, you've coped with a lot already. You
can handle this, too. So you might as well get on with it.''
   Because of the expensive chemotherapy and two operations to
remove tumors, Ms. Jorgensen had to sell her 3,000-square foot
Laguna Niguel home. She and her 7-year-old terrier, Bonnie, have
been living in a three-bedroom apartment here.
   Ms. Jorgensen's story made world headlines 37 years ago when she
went to Copenhagen, Denmark, as George Jorgensen Jr. and returned
as Christine Jorgensen.
   With the unanticipated limelight, she joined the lecture and
nightclub circuit, authored books, met royalty and celebrities,
found new gentlemen friends and ended up with enough money, jewels
and furs to provide a comfortable lifestyle.
   Ms. Jorgensen insists she has no regrets about the operation and
is proud to have been part of the sexual revolution.
   She acknowledged time has taken its toll. ``Getting myself
together takes a little more effort these days.''
   But it's also had its advantages, she said. ``I'm not that
recognizable anymore. I can actually go into a supermarket and
people don't know who I am, which is just wonderful and suits me
just fine.''
   Despite her time-consuming treatments, Ms. Jorgensen said she
still has time for reading and preparing her second autobiography.
   She hopes to work with other cancer patients someday, she said,
but added: ``Cancer is quite unforgiving. It's the kind of thing
that prevents you from making terribly long-range plans.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
