<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Boeing-BallBearings     09-03 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing-Ball Bearings,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Safety Probe Reported Into Boeing Ball Bearings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials are investigating whether
airline safety has been threatened by more than 2,000 ball bearings
used in Boeing 737, 747 and 757 jetliners manufactured in the last
two years, it was reported Friday.
   A lawsuit filed in federal court last week by an airplane parts
manufacturing company alleged the ball bearings were counterfeit.
   ``Is there a safety problem?'' David Duff, a Federal Aviation
Administration spokesman in Seattle, told the Los Angeles Times in
an article published Friday. ``That is our main concern. If we
identify anything in that area, we will take care of it
immediately.''
   Boeing spokesman William Clark acknowledged that FAA
investigators had met with Boeing officials Thursday, but declined
to reveal details.
   ``Beyond that, you're going to need to go to them to find out
their future plans,'' he said.
   Boeing has declined to say how many jets manufactured after July
1, 1986, contain the allegedly bogus bearings, or which airlines
bought the planes.
   Since July 1, 1986, Boeing has manufactured 490 Boeing 737, 747
and 757 aircraft, the company said. That works out to about 20
percent of the Boeing planes of these types in use worldwide.
   The Boeing jet that crashed Wednesday in Dallas was a 727.
</TEXT>
