<DOCNO> AP880903-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 0114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Engine-History     09-03 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Engine-History,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Reports: No History of Accidents For Engines</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Delta Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OWEN CANFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Engines similar to those on the Delta Air
Lines jet that crashed in Dallas have malfunctioned 28 times in the
past five years but have not caused any accidents, Federal Aviation
Administration records show.
   The Pratt & Whitney JT8D Model 15 engines have failed on
liftoff, suffered minor explosions during takeoff and vibrated in
flight, according to records provided Friday by the FAA's office in
Oklahoma City.
   Investigators of Wednesday's crash at the Dallas-Fort Worth
International are studying the Boeing 727 jet's three engines and
the position of its wing flaps as they search for the cause of the
crash that killed 13 people.
   Bobbie Mardis of the FAA's public affairs office said the FAA
records covered five years. ``We asked for a printout of accidents
or incidents where the JT8D-15 was a contributing factor to
whatever happened,'' she said.
   On the printout, drawn from the FAA's accident-incident report,
each example was listed as an incident.
   ``There were no accidents as a result of engine problems,''
according to the computer, Ms. Mardis said.
   In one case, takeoff was aborted when a Douglass DC-9 leaving a
New York airport in June 1983 lost power in the right engine,
causing smoke and flames to come out of the engine. The report said
the cause was ``third stage turbine failure.''
   As a Boeing 727 was taking off from an Ohio airport in April of
this year, a loud bang was heard. ``The number three engine turbine
had failed with parts spraying on runway. Takeoff aborted. No
fire,'' the report said.
   In April 1984, an explosion occurred in an engine during the
takeoff and initial climb of a Boeing 727, causing a loss of the
hydraulic system.
   In November 1983, a Boeing 727 jetliner in New York had its No.
3 engine fail on liftoff. After returning, mechanics found the rear
turbine blade broken off and the engine was replaced, the report
said.
   Other problems listed were engines overheating, engines shutting
down for various reasons and oil pressure fluctuation.
</TEXT>
