<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LandingMiscue     09-03 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Landing Miscue,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>America West Airlines Jetliner Nearly Lands at Wrong Field</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURANGO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An America West Airlines jetliner carrying
38 passengers nearly landed at a small airport before the pilot
recognized the mistake and pulled out 1,000 feet above the narrow
runway, it was reported Friday.
   The Boeing 737 landed safely Thursday night at the larger
Durango-La Plata County Airport, its correct destination, five
miles to the east of Animas Air Park.
   The Federal Aviation Administration began investigating the
incident involving Flight 1240 after inquiries by the Durango
Herald, which reported the mixup.
   America West also is investigating the incident, said Kathy
Christianson, manager of corporate communications for the
Phoenix-based airline.
   The Durango airport has no tower, so the two pilots were
following instruments, she said. ``The pilots did what we call a
fly-around and landed at the Durango airport.''
   John Ford, an apprentice mechanic at Animas Air Park who was an
eyewitness, said it appeared the aircraft was going to land at the
air park.
   Ford said air park officials didn't radio the jet but the pilot
pulled out of the landing pattern himself, apparently realizing the
mistake.
   The runway was clear at the time and a landing posed no danger
to people on the ground. However, the wide-bodied jet would have
encountered severe complications if it tried to land, Ford said,
noting the runway is only 50 feet wide and shorter than the
commercial airport's.
   ``If he knew what he was doing he could have pulled it off,'' he
said, but the landing would be possible only if the pilot were
aware of the runway's smaller size.
   Sue vonKersburg was walking her dog near Animas Air Park when
she noticed the plane's lights in the distance.
   ``I realized it was quite a large plane. I could see writing on
the fuselage. ... Then I heard him start to give it power. I knew
he had made a mistake before he did,'' vonKersburg said.
   She said she called America West at the Durango-La Plata County
Airport to report the incident and was told the airline already had
received five calls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
