<HEAD>World War I Grenade Turned In Under Amnesty Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FERNDOWN, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 84-year-old woman delivered a World
War I hand grenade to police Friday under Britain's month-long
amnesty program designed to collect illegal firearms.
   ``Can I turn this in, please?'' the woman asked officers as she
removed the grenade from her shopping bag at the Dorset police
station in Ferndown, 117 miles southwest of London.
   Police did not identify the woman but quoted her as saying the
grenade, which still was intact with explosives and the activator
pin, had been on the mantelpiece in her home for years. They did
not say how or when she had acquired the deadly device.
   The amnesty is intended to give people a chance to surrender
illegal weapons before new laws take effect that would strengthen
Britain's present weapons-control measures, among the toughest in
the world.
   Other weapons turned in since the amnesty program began Thursday
included a submachine gun and a crossbow.
