<DOCNO> AP880903-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-03-88 0204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LowRiver     09-03 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Low River,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Lifts Barge Limits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barge traffic moved smoothly but slowly on
the lower Mississippi River on Friday, prompting the Coast Guard to
relax restrictions on towboat loads imposed because of low water.
   ``We've gotten to the point where we have a very stable
channel,'' said Michael Donohoe, commander of the Coast Guard
district from Caruthersville, Mo., to Greenville, Miss.
   Towboat operators, restricted to a maximum of 16 barges since
June, will likely increase their loads to 20 barges and some may go
to 25, Donohoe said.
   Towboats on the lower Mississippi often push 25 barges this time
of year and in high water can handle 30 to 40. Barge operators say
they will lose $200 million this year because of the low water
caused by this year's severe drought.
   The Coast Guard also limited barges to drafts of 8.5 feet,
meaning the weight of their loads had to be limited. The barges
generally draw nine feet of water.
   The drought caused the river to drop more than 20 feet below
normal at Memphis in July.
   It still was 12 feet below normal Friday at Memphis, but Donohoe
said dredging by the Army Corps of Engineers and successes in
keeping towboat traffic moving have reduced the worst shoaling in
the river.
   The shipping channel is at least 11 feet deep throughout the
375-mile Memphis district, he said.
   The Coast Guard said 126 groundings have been reported in the
Memphis district since the first of June, with 41 occurring in a
single week in July.
</TEXT>
