<1ST_LINE>a w AM-FarmerPower ADV05   09-03 1186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmer Power, ADV 05,1218</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Sept. 5, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Drought Hasn't Dried Up Political Punch of Farm Bloc in Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American farmers, dwindling in number,
stricken by drought and plagued by chronic money woes, are proving
they can still produce a bumper crop of political power on Capitol
Hill.
   ``Farmers have got the votes and they get pandered to because
they've got the votes,'' says Rep. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla., one of just
29 House members who voted against this summer's $3.9 billion
drought relief legislation.
   Most lawmakers said farmers deserved help after drought wrecked
37 percent of the corn crop, 23 percent of the soybeans and tore
into the harvest of spring wheat. Most also agree the price tag
looks bigger than it is _ because it falls within the amount the
government stands to save because of drought.
   Three factors powered the bill from the hopper to the
president's desk in less than a month. One was the traditional
American generosity toward hard-pressed family farmers. Lawmakers
cited it repeatedly.
   ``In this country we have a tradition of helping someone who
through no fault of his own winds up behind the eight ball,'' says
Rep. Edward R. Madigan, R-Ill., the top Republican on the House
Agriculture Committee.
   ``There is the presumption that farming as a way of life is
somehow morally superior,'' Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., a critic of
farm spending, declares caustically.
   Another factor that fuels farm bills, officials said, was a keen
awareness that blocs of farm voters can swing close elections in
many states. Politicians often trace the 1986 unseating of Sens.
James Abnor, R-S.D., and Mark Andrews, R-N.D., to dissatisfaction
with the farm economy.
   ``Every senator has some agriculture in his state,'' observers
House minority counsel Hyde Murray, a longtime observer of farm
politics. He says lawmakers who must pay close heed to the wishes
of such voters number well over 100 in the 435-member House.
   Such pressures were at work not only in shaping the drought
legislation but a wide-ranging 1985 blueprint for snapping the farm
economy out of stagnation that plagued it throughout the early
1980s.
   While revitalizing markets, the measure also sent the cost of
subsidies to a 1986 peak of $26 billion and sent million-dollar
payments to corporate farmers.
   Widespread complaints about the cost resulted in a decision by
Congress to cap most individual payments at $50,000 and a few
exceptions at $250,000. Approval of programs was preceded by heavy
lobbying among producers groups.
   Likewise, the drought bill signed by President Reagan on Aug. 11
contains an about-face in dairy policy that will cost taxpayers an
estimated $185 million to $200 million. Approval of the provisions
represented a distinct victory for dairy farmers.
   Such measures are as old as Congress. Indeed, farm programs go
back to colonial times and the marble columns resembling corn
stalks and tobacco plants in the Capitol vestibule suggest
farming's special place.
   Price supports _ a floor under crop prices with government
serving as the buyer of last resort _ arrived with the Depression
and now form the bedrock of U.S. farm policy. Since then, Congress
also has spawned income supports, conservation payments and export
subsidies to keep farmers afloat.
   As farm numbers have dwindled, however, some farm groups have
increasingly adopted campaign contributions to help make their
voice heard in Washington.
   ``I think statements that farmers always get their way are
overblown,'' says agricultural consultant William Lesher. ``But
there are exceptions.''
   ``Sugar and dairy are two tough ones,'' he says. ``They just
seem to do their jobs and get their way. I think it has to do with
campaign contributions and I think it has more to do with the size
of their campaign contributions than with their persuasiveness in
making their case.''
   Huge dairy cooperatives have led all of agriculture in campaign
contributions for a decade and plunged millions of dollars into
House and Senate races. In the last two years, the Dallas-based
Associated Milk Producers Inc. has contributed $349,950 to 195
candidates.
   It gave a total of $891,950 to candidates in the 1986 election
to rank 23rd among the 3,187 groups registered with the Federal
Election Commission.
   By comparison, the National Association of Realtors, reported
$2,751,588 in contributions to 1986 campaigns to rank No.1, and 16
groups in all handed out $1 million or more in political donations
that year.
   The No.2 co-op, Mid-America Dairymen Inc., has contributed
$241,400 to 225 candidates over the last two years. It donated
$467,500 to 1986 campaigns to rank 47th among groups registered
with the Federal Election Commission.
   Four of the five top cooperatives contributing to 1986
candidates were dairy groups. They gave a total of $1,680,168.
Sixteen of the top 50 cooperatives were dairy groups, according to
commission records.
   ``Our dairy farmers out there have a lot of cows,'' says
Mid-America lobbyist Frank Vacca. ``And those cows are their
producers. I like to say that I've got 535 producers up here'' on
Capitol Hill.
   ``We're here to represent our constituents who are good
producers and if we have some good producing congressmen and
senators and presidents and we can help them by contributing to
their campaigns, what's wrong with that?''
   Congress produced for dairy farmers in the drought bill,
canceling a cut in price supports of 50 cents for each 100 pounds
of milk and imposing instead a temporary, three-month increase of
50 cents per hundredweight.
   Critics also often grumble that campaign contributions are vital
in helping sugar producers to maintain import restrictions that
raise prices considerably for American consumers.
   ``There's little question that campaign contributions have
sweetened the pot of support for the sugar program in Congress,''
says Ellen Haas, executive director of Washington-based Public
Voice for Food and Health Policy.
   She noted in a report issued in 1986 that on a key vote to ease
import curbs 263 members voting against the measure had received
received a total of $743,021 in campaign funds from 18 sugar-grower
organizations over the previous four years. The 142 voting to lift
restrictions had reaped only $85,300 in such contributions.
   Votes on the auction block? Nonsense, farm lawmakers say.
   ``It's totally absurd and insulting, really, to those of us who
have been friends of the sugar industry,'' says House Agriculture
Committee Chairman E. ``Kika'' de la Garza, D-Texas, some of whose
homefolks are cane producers.
   ``If I have to choose between the Rio Grande Valley and some
foreign country, you can imagine which one I'll choose,'' he adds.
   Reagan administration efforts since then to budge sugar tariffs,
however, have come to nought.
   ``Nothing has happened with our bill,'' says Richard W.
Goldberg, acting undersecretary of agriculture for international
activities and commodity programs. ``There's just insufficient
support to get it moving.''
   He says the reason is that so many Agriculture Committee members
have sugar producers in their district and almost all of them have
constituents who grow corn _ whose price is closely linked to that
of sugar.
   ``They kind of help each other,'' says Goldberg.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Sept. 5</NOTE>
