<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 03-04,0787</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept. 3-4</NOTE>
<HEAD>Cocoa Glut Lends Crisis Tone To International Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be followed later in session with an ADD containing
weekly price trends</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Commodity traders are betting on a breakdown of the glutted
cocoa market's sputtering price-support machine as the 38
nation-members of the International Cocoa Organization prepare for
two weeks of talks in London.
   With cocoa prices at 12-year lows, supplies at an all-time high
and the world's top producer threatening to pull out of the
price-support agreement, a crisis atmosphere likely will prevail at
Monday's opening session of the ICCO's semi-annual meeting,
analysts said.
   Blend in the ICCO secretariat's recommendation to suspend levies
on cocoa sales _ the primary financial support of the
producer-consumer cooperative _ and ``things are looking pretty
awful'' for cocoa bulls, said Sandra Kaul, cocoa market analyst
with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   ``There are expectations that these meetings are going to break
down, that they will come up with no new means of price support and
that they are going to suspend the call for producer levies,'' she
said.
   Cocoa prices generally have been falling since early 1984, when
it became apparent that production during the October
1983-September 1984 crop year would significantly exceed demand.
   The surplus has risen each year since then. Arthur Stevenson,
cocoa market analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.,
estimated that world cocoa stocks on Sept. 30, the end of the
current crop year, will stand at 705,000 metric tons, compared with
594,000 metric tons last year.
   Stocks are expected to increase to nearly 900,000 metric tons,
an all-time high, in the upcoming crop year, he said. A metric ton
is about 2,205 pounds.
   ``That is a massive, massive burden overhanging the market,''
Stevenson said in a telephone interview. Cocoa consumption,
meanwhile, ``has been going up only very slowly,'' he said.
   The surplus has weighed heavily on prices. The price for
near-month delivery of cocoa on New York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa
Exchange has fallen from about $2,800 a metric ton in early January
1984 to $1,202 on Friday.
   The drop in cocoa prices has had little impact on chocolate-bar
prices because cocoa is a relatively small ingredient in chocolate
confections, Stevenson said. Candy bar prices also reflect
manufacturers' costs for milk, sugar, packaging and marketing.
   Besides, Stevenson said, ``if people eat one chocolate bar a
week, they're not going to start eating five chocolate bars a week
because prices are marginally lower.''
   Yet cocoa-growing countries keep increasing their output, hoping
to make up for lower prices by selling more.
   The ICCO is supposed to help support prices by buying surplus
cocoa and keeping it off the market in a ``buffer stock.'' But the
current ICCO agreement, which began in 1987 and runs through
September 1990, limits the buffer stock to 250,000 metric tons and
it is already at that level, Stevenson said.
   Even if ICCO members should agree to increase the buffer-stock
limit, the organization would still be strapped for cash with which
to buy the cocoa.
   The agreement requires cocoa-producing countries to pay the ICCO
a $30 levy on every ton of cocoa they export. But the largest
producers, including the Ivory Coast and Brazil, have stopped
paying the levies.
   Producers owe the ICCO about $70 million in levies, of which at
least $48 million is owed by the Ivory Coast, analysts said.
   The ICCO secretariat has proposed to do away with the levies, a
suggestion that will be debated at the London meeting. But analysts
say the secretariat's proposed alternative _ selling some of the
buffer-stock cocoa to finance ICCO operations _ would only drive
prices down further and exacerabte the problem.
   Stevenson said some producer nations have suggested that all
producers withhold some cocoa from the market to drive up prices.
That idea is not likely to fly, he said, because it is opposed by
other producers, including No. 2 Brazil.
   The Ivory Coast is the world's top cocoa producer. Last year, it
produced 590,000 metric tons of cocoa, or 29 percent of the world
supply.
   This past week, Ivory Coast officials reportedly said the ICCO
was dying and that unless solutions to the market's dilemmas were
found, it would withdraw from the ICCO at the end of the current
agreement.
   But analysts saw no easy solutions.
   ``The ICCO agreement simply cannot circumvent supply-demand
realties,'' Stevenson said. ``The agreement does not have control
where it is most needed. It cannot cut back on production, nor can
it boost consumption.''
</TEXT>
