<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     09-03 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Higher Jobless Rate Is Good News On Wall Street</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A setback for job seekers was good news for
investors as a rise in the unemployment rate eased inflation fears
and sent stock and bond prices sharply higher.
   The Labor Department's report Friday of a rise in the civilian
jobless rate to 5.6 percent in August stirred the biggest rise in
the Treasury bond and note market since Oct. 22, a few days after
the stock market crash.
   The higher jobless rate calmed a market that has been worried
for months that the economy was growing too quickly and might go
into an inflationary spiral.
   ``It's bad news, I guess, for job searchers, but it's not
necessarily bad news for consumers in general,'' said George
Iwanicki, an associate economist for Kidder, Peabody & Co.
   Stock prices leaped and the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial
stocks rose 52.28 points to 2,054.59, its biggest increase since a
74.68-point gain on May 31.
   The rise of more than 50 points triggered a restriction on
member firms' use of computers for a form of program trading. The
restrictions were designed to avoid chaotic swings in stock prices.
   While the overall Treasury market had its biggest rise of 1988,
the Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond staged its
second-biggest rally of the year.
   The price of the Treasury's 30-year bond rose $25.90 per $1,000
face amount, driving its yield down to 9.04 from 9.30 percent late
Thursday. The only bigger rally of 1988 was a $26.25 price increase
on Jan. 15, after the government reported a big drop in the trade
deficit.
   The bond market is highly sensitive to inflation and takes
weaker growth as good news. When bond prices rose, investors moved
to the stock market in search of bargains.
   In the long run, a slight increase in joblessness could mean
more stable, prolonged growth, said David Bennett, a market analyst
at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   In spite of the uptick in the jobless rate, from 5.4 percent in
July and a 14-year low of 5.3 percent in May, the economy continues
to be expanding and the nation is not far from full employment,
Iwanicki said.
   ``Fundamentally, the economy is quite strong,'' said Helen
Hotchkiss, a senior economist at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Analysts said the slight increase in the jobless level eases
pressure on the Federal Reserve to move before the election to
raise its discount rate, which is the interest rate it charges on
loans to member banks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
